-- Narration scripts for the 40 national-core lessons.
--
-- Generated by 4 parallel revision agents that converted the markdown
-- bodies into TTS-ready prose:
--   - No markdown formatting
--   - Em-dashes for natural breath pauses
--   - Bullet lists collapsed into one-concept-per-paragraph sequences
--   - Section headers folded into transition phrases
--   - Abbreviations spelled out on first use (mph → miles per hour)
--   - Short sentences over long
--   - Every fact, number, and safety rule preserved
--
-- The script lives on the lesson row alongside body. The narration
-- pipeline (free MeloTTS today; ElevenLabs once the key is set) reads
-- narrationScript when present, and the rendered audio is cached on
-- narrationAudioR2Key with a generated-at timestamp.
--
-- School copies (school_lesson) inherit narrationScript via the
-- existing pack-install copy logic; schools can edit or override per
-- their voice.

UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Traffic signs are a visual language. Once you learn the grammar — shape and color — you can read most signs in a fraction of a second, even before you can make out the words. That speed matters. At 45 miles per hour — you cover about 66 feet every second. So a sign you can''t decode fast is a sign you''ve already driven past.

Now, the shape of a sign is a clue to its purpose. You can recognize it from far away, in fog, or when it''s partly blocked by a tree.

Octagon. Eight sides. That means stop. It''s the only sign with that shape. If you ever see the back of an octagon — you know without thinking that drivers on the other side have a stop.

Upside-down triangle. That''s yield. Slow down. Be ready to stop. Give the right-of-way.

Diamond. That''s a warning. Something ahead could surprise you, like a curve, a deer crossing, or a narrow bridge.

Pentagon. That''s the school shape. School zone or school crossing.

Pennant — the long horizontal triangle — marks a no-passing zone. It''s posted on the left side of the road.

A tall rectangle is regulatory, like speed limits or one-way.

A wide rectangle is a guide sign, like directions and distances.

A round sign is the railroad crossing advance warning.

And the crossbuck — that''s the X shape — marks the actual railroad crossing. Treat it like a yield sign at minimum.

Color adds another layer of meaning so you don''t have to read every word.

Red means stop, yield, or prohibition. Do not enter. Wrong way.

Yellow is general warning. Caution ahead.

Fluorescent yellow-green is a warning specifically about people. School zones. Pedestrian crossings. Bike crossings.

Orange means construction or temporary work zones. Take these seriously. Lanes shift. Workers are nearby. And fines often double.

Green is for guidance and directions. Exits, distances, street names.

Blue points to driver services. Hospitals, rest areas, gas, food, lodging.

Brown signals recreation and points of interest. Parks and historic sites.

White with black letters is regulatory, like speed limits.

Here''s the thing about regulatory signs — they are laws, not suggestions. A regulatory sign tells you something you legally must or must not do. The classics work like this.

Stop. A full stop behind the line. Then you proceed when safe. Rolling through is illegal — and a common cause of T-bone crashes.

Yield. Slow, look, and let cross traffic or pedestrians go first. You only need to stop if conditions require it.

Speed limit. That''s the maximum legal speed in ideal conditions. In rain, snow, fog, or heavy traffic — the safe speed is lower. And you''re still responsible for driving to conditions.

Do Not Enter and Wrong Way. You''re about to enter a road going against traffic. Stop. Back out carefully if you can. Find another route.

One Way. Traffic flows in the direction of the arrow only.

No Turn on Red. Even when the light is red and the way looks clear — you cannot turn.

Warning signs buy you reaction time. Warning signs — mostly yellow diamonds — give you advance notice so you can adjust before you reach the hazard. A curve sign often comes with an advisory speed in black on yellow. That speed isn''t a legal limit. But it''s a strong recommendation based on how the curve was engineered. Ignoring it is how cars end up in ditches.

Here are common warning signs to recognize. Curve and sharp turn arrows. Merge and lane-ends. Two-way traffic ahead, which shows up after a divided section ends. Slippery when wet. Deer, cattle, or other animal crossings. Pedestrian and bicycle crossings. And hill — steep grade ahead.

Guide and service signs do different jobs. Green guide signs help with navigation. Blue service signs help with logistics. Neither carries a legal requirement. But they reduce stress and prevent last-second lane changes when you''re hunting for an exit. Plan your exits a mile ahead — not at the gore point.

Finally, signs work as a system. Signs often come in groups. A warning sign sets up the situation. A regulatory sign tells you the rule. A guide sign confirms where you''re going. Train yourself to scan all three on every block. Good drivers don''t react to signs. They anticipate them.' WHERE id = 'lesson_signs-and-signals_reading-traffic-signs';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'A traffic signal is more than a colored light. It''s an instruction, a timer, and a coordination tool that lets thousands of cars share an intersection without crashing. Knowing exactly what each phase means — and what to do during transitions — separates safe drivers from the ones who cause fender-benders at every light.

Let''s start with the basic phases.

Steady red. Stop behind the marked line, the crosswalk, or before the intersection if no line exists. Remain stopped until the light changes. Or, where allowed, until you can safely turn right on red after a complete stop.

Steady yellow. The light is about to turn red. Stop if you can do so safely. Yellow is not speed up.

Steady green. You may proceed if the intersection is clear. Green is permission — not a guarantee that the way is safe.

Flashing red. Treat it exactly like a stop sign. Stop. Yield. Then go when safe.

Flashing yellow. Slow down and proceed with caution. Cross traffic may not have to stop.

Arrows tell you what''s protected. Green arrows give you a protected movement. That means conflicting traffic and pedestrians have a red light and shouldn''t be in your path. A solid green ball is different. It only gives you a permissive movement for turns. You must yield to oncoming traffic and pedestrians before turning.

A flashing yellow arrow is a newer signal. It means you may turn — but you must yield. It replaced the old habit of using a green ball for permissive lefts, because too many drivers assumed they had the right-of-way.

A red arrow means stop for that specific movement. In most places — you cannot turn on a red arrow even when right-on-red is allowed for the rest of the intersection.

Now, what do you do when the light is out? If a signal is dark, flashing red in all directions, or visibly malfunctioning — treat the intersection as an all-way stop. Every driver stops. The first to arrive goes first. When two drivers arrive at the same time, the driver on the right goes first.

Here''s the big idea about right-of-way. It''s given, not taken. Right-of-way rules tell you who must yield, not who has a guaranteed pass. You can be legally in the right and still be in a hospital bed. Yield when in doubt.

The core rules go like this.

At an uncontrolled intersection — no signs, no signals — yield to the vehicle on your right if you arrive at the same time.

When turning left — yield to oncoming traffic and to pedestrians in the crosswalk you''re turning into.

At a T-intersection — the road that ends must yield to through traffic.

When entering a roadway from a driveway, alley, or parking lot — yield to all traffic and pedestrians on the road.

Pedestrians in a crosswalk — marked or unmarked at intersections — generally have right-of-way over vehicles.

Emergency vehicles with lights and sirens have right-of-way over everyone. Pull to the right and stop if you can.

School buses with flashing reds and an extended stop arm require traffic in both directions to stop on undivided roads.

Funeral processions are typically allowed to proceed through intersections together — even on a red — if led by an escort.

Pedestrian signals work in parallel with vehicle lights. Walk and don''t-walk signals — and the newer countdown timers — are designed for pedestrians. But they tell you a lot too. A flashing don''t walk, or a low countdown, means the light is about to change. If you''re approaching — expect a yellow soon and prepare to stop. Not to floor it.

Now, some common signal mistakes to avoid.

Stopping in the crosswalk. Stop behind the line so pedestrians have the space they''re entitled to.

Creeping into the intersection on a left turn and getting stuck on red. Only enter the intersection when you can clear it. Otherwise you''ll block cross traffic.

Assuming a green light means go. Always glance left, then right, then left again. Red-light runners cause some of the deadliest urban crashes.

Treating a yellow as a challenge. The honest test is — can I stop safely? If yes, stop. If braking hard would risk a rear-end collision, continue through carefully.

Here''s the bigger picture. Signals work because everyone follows them. The moment a driver decides the rules don''t apply to them — the whole system breaks down. Drive like the person in the next car is depending on you to behave predictably. Because they are.' WHERE id = 'lesson_signs-and-signals_traffic-signals-and-right-of-way';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Pavement markings are the lines, arrows, and words painted on the road surface. They guide you when signs and signals aren''t visible — especially at night when your headlights catch the reflective paint long before you''d see a sign. Like signs, the markings follow a consistent code. Once you know it, you can drive confidently on roads you''ve never seen before.

Let''s talk about line colors. Line color tells you about the relationship between you and oncoming traffic.

Yellow lines separate traffic moving in opposite directions. If a yellow line is on your left — you''re on a two-way road.

White lines separate traffic moving in the same direction. Or they mark the edge of the road on the right.

Here''s a warning. If you ever see a yellow line on your right while driving forward — you''re on the wrong side of the road. Stop and reorient immediately.

Now, line patterns. They tell you what you''re allowed to do.

Solid line. Do not cross unless you''re making a legal turn into or out of a driveway, alley, or parking spot.

Broken — or dashed — line. Crossing is permitted when safe. That''s for passing and lane changes.

Double solid line. Strong prohibition. Do not cross. Used on two-way roads where passing is dangerous, and on freeway shoulders.

One solid plus one broken. Passing is allowed only from the side with the broken line. If the solid line is on your side — no passing.

Edge lines and shoulders work a little differently. The white edge line on the right marks the boundary between the travel lane and the shoulder. A solid white edge line means the shoulder is for emergencies only. On many roads — the line becomes broken to mark a turn lane or merge area.

A yellow edge line on the left of a one-way road marks the left boundary. You''ll see this on divided highways, and on the entry side of one-way streets.

There are also special lane markings to recognize.

Turn lanes. These are marked by arrows on the pavement and overhead or roadside signs. Only make the movement indicated by the arrow. A left arrow means turn left only. A straight-and-left arrow means either is allowed.

Two-way left-turn lanes. That''s a center lane bordered by a solid yellow line on the outside and a broken yellow line on the inside. Either direction of traffic can use it — but only for turning left, or for entering the road from a side street. It''s not a passing lane. It''s not a travel lane.

High-occupancy vehicle lanes — often called H-O-V lanes — are usually marked with a white diamond. They''re restricted to vehicles with a minimum number of occupants during posted hours.

Bike lanes. Solid white lines, often with a bicycle symbol. Don''t drive in them except to turn across them. And yield to cyclists when you do.

Bus and transit lanes are marked and often colored. Restricted to authorized vehicles.

Now, crosswalks and stop lines.

The stop line is a solid white bar across your lane. Stop behind it at a red light or stop sign. The line marks where the intersection legally begins.

The crosswalk is marked by two parallel white lines, or by a ladder pattern of white stripes. Pedestrians have right-of-way here. And even where no lines are painted — every intersection has a legal crosswalk along the natural path of the sidewalk.

The yield line is a row of white triangles — sometimes called shark teeth — across your lane. Slow. Look. And yield.

Words and symbols painted on the pavement back up signs. Here are common ones.

STOP or YIELD painted ahead of the line where the sign sits.

SCHOOL in front of a school zone.

ONLY with an arrow, meaning the lane is exclusively for that movement.

P-E-D X-I-N-G for pedestrian crossing.

R-R with an X marking a railroad crossing.

And arrows showing allowed turns and lane direction.

Reading markings at night and in bad weather takes extra effort. Lane paint is engineered to reflect headlights. But rain, snow, and worn paint can hide it. In those conditions — slow down and follow the path of vehicles ahead at a safe distance. Use the edge line on the right as your reference, rather than the center line, which may be obscured by other cars. And don''t assume a missing line means you can go anywhere. The road still has lanes. You just can''t see them.

Good drivers read pavement markings constantly — the same way they read signs. They become a backup when signs are obscured. And a primary cue when they aren''t.' WHERE id = 'lesson_signs-and-signals_pavement-markings';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Some areas have their own special package of signs, signals, and markings because the risks are higher than average. Work zones, school zones, and railroad crossings are the three you''ll meet most often. Each has its own rhythm. And each demands more attention — not less.

Let''s start with work zones. Work zones change the road. Lanes shift. Lanes disappear. Speed limits drop. And people are walking around just feet from moving traffic. Crashes in work zones often injure the workers — not just the drivers.

Here are the key signs and signals to recognize.

Orange diamond warning signs. Road Work Ahead. Lane Closed. Flagger Ahead. These give you time to slow down and merge.

Reduced speed limit signs. Often posted as Work Zone Speed Limit. These are legally enforceable, and many places double fines.

Channelizing devices. Cones, barrels, and drums guide you through shifts in lane alignment. Stay between them. Do not weave.

Flaggers. A flagger''s hand signals override signs and signals. A red flag or a STOP paddle means stop. A SLOW paddle means proceed slowly through the zone.

Arrow boards and message signs. These tell you which lane is closing, and how far ahead.

Now, how do you actually drive a work zone? Merge early when you see the warning signs. Late merging causes chain-reaction braking.

Increase your following distance. The car ahead may brake hard for a worker or equipment.

Watch for stopped vehicles. Rear-end crashes are the most common type in work zones.

Don''t change lanes inside the cones unless markings allow it.

And put your phone away. Work zones are not the place to glance at a text.

School zones are next. School zones protect kids who don''t always make rational traffic decisions. They run into the road for a dropped ball. They cross between parked cars. They look the wrong way.

Here are the school-zone cues to watch for.

The pentagon-shaped school sign marks a school ahead.

Fluorescent yellow-green crossing signs mark crossings used by students.

School zone speed limit signs are often combined with flashing yellow beacons. The reduced limit applies whenever the lights are flashing — or during posted times — or when children are present, depending on the wording.

Crossing guards. Their directions have the force of law. Stop when they hold up a stop paddle, even if the light is green.

School buses with flashing red lights and an extended stop arm. All traffic in both directions on undivided roads must stop. On a divided highway — traffic going the opposite way is usually exempt. But check the signs in your area before assuming.

Now, driving rules in school zones.

Obey the posted reduced speed limit whenever it applies. Speeding tickets in school zones are usually steep.

Scan continuously for kids between parked cars, at corners, and on bikes.

Never pass a stopped vehicle that may be yielding to a pedestrian in a crosswalk. Stop too. The other driver may be seeing something you can''t.

Drop-off and pickup zones have their own rules. Follow posted signs and any school staff directing traffic.

Finally — railroad crossings. A train can take more than a mile to stop. The driver of a train cannot swerve. If you and a train arrive at the crossing at the same time — the train wins, every time. And the outcome is often fatal.

Here are the railroad-crossing cues.

The round yellow advance warning sign with an X and the letters R-R means a crossing is ahead. Slow down and look for the crossing itself.

Pavement markings. A large white X with the letters R-R painted in the lane.

The crossbuck — the white X-shaped sign — marks the crossing. Treat it as a yield sign at minimum. Stop if a train is approaching.

The number-of-tracks sign is posted below the crossbuck. If it says 2 — look both ways twice. A second train can be hidden by the first.

Flashing red lights and bells mean a train is coming, or already on the crossing. Stop at least 15 feet from the nearest rail. Wait until the lights stop and the gates rise fully.

Gates. Never drive around lowered gates. It is illegal — and often deadly.

Here is how to cross safely. Slow down as you approach. Lower your radio and turn off the fan so you can hear horns or bells. Look both ways down the tracks, not just at the signals. Equipment can fail.

If your view is blocked — edge forward only until you can see clearly. Once you start across — do not stop. Make sure there''s room on the far side before you cross.

If your vehicle stalls on the tracks — get everyone out and away from the tracks immediately. Walk toward the train at an angle, so debris from a collision flies away from you. Then call the emergency number posted at the crossing.

There''s a common thread across all of these. Work zones, school zones, and railroad crossings all share one feature. The consequences of inattention are much worse than the inconvenience of being careful. Slow down. Scan more. And assume something unexpected is about to happen. That mindset is what keeps drivers — and everyone around them — alive.' WHERE id = 'lesson_signs-and-signals_work-zones-school-zones-and-railroad-crossings';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Right-of-way is one of the most misunderstood ideas in driving. People talk about it like it''s a prize you win at an intersection. It isn''t. Right-of-way is the rule that decides who is supposed to move next, so that two cars — or a car and a person, or a car and a bike — don''t try to use the same space at the same time.

Here''s the key idea you need to lock in early. The law tells you who must yield — not who has the right to take. No driver ever truly has the right-of-way. They are only given it when other road users yield it to them. That difference sounds small. But it changes how you drive. A driver who thinks it''s my turn, go — causes crashes. A driver who thinks is everyone actually yielding to me? — avoids them.

Why do these rules exist? Traffic works because drivers can predict what other drivers will do. Right-of-way rules are the shared script. When everyone follows the same script — intersections clear smoothly. When someone improvises — rolling a stop sign, swinging wide through a roundabout, waving another driver through out of turn — the script breaks. And people get hurt.

Three things make right-of-way rules so important.

First — intersections are where most urban crashes happen. Paths cross there. Speeds drop and rise. Drivers are deciding, looking, and turning all at once.

Second — vulnerable road users have the least protection. Pedestrians, cyclists, and people using wheelchairs or scooters lose every collision with a car. The rules tilt in their favor for a reason.

Third — eye contact is not a contract. You may think the other driver saw you. They may be looking at their phone, their kid, or right through you. Assume nothing until the car actually slows.

There is a general hierarchy for right-of-way. When you''re not sure who goes — work down this list in order.

First. Emergency vehicles with lights and sirens. Everyone yields, pulls right when safe, and stops.

Second. Traffic signals and signs. A red light or stop sign overrides almost any other rule.

Third. Pedestrians in or entering a crosswalk. Marked or unmarked — they get to cross.

Fourth. Vehicles already in the intersection. If someone is already through — let them finish.

Fifth. The driver on the right, when two cars arrive at the same time at an uncontrolled intersection or all-way stop.

Sixth. Through traffic over turning traffic. Left-turning drivers yield to oncoming cars going straight.

This list isn''t a magic spell. But it covers most situations you will see for years.

Here''s something important. Yielding is an action — not a feeling. Yielding means slowing down, stopping if needed, and letting the other road user go before you do. It is something you do with the brake and the steering wheel. Not just something you think. A common teen mistake is to ease forward while yielding, which signals to the other driver that you''re going. Either commit to stopping, or commit to going. Half-decisions confuse everyone.

What about when the other driver is wrong? Sometimes you legally have the right-of-way, and the other driver takes it anyway. Maybe they rolled the stop. Maybe they cut across three lanes. Your job in that moment is not to prove a point. It''s to avoid the crash. Brake. Steer. Or both. You can be 100% legally right and still end up in the hospital. A defensive driver gives up right-of-way whenever holding onto it would cause a collision.

Now, here''s how to read an intersection before you reach it. Good drivers start solving the intersection before they arrive. As you approach, ask yourself a few questions.

What kind of control is here? Signal, stop sign, yield sign, nothing?

Who else is approaching, and from where?

Are there pedestrians at the corners or in the crosswalks?

Is anyone signaling a turn?

Is the lane I want actually clear past the intersection? Or will I get stuck blocking it?

If you can answer those five questions before you''re at the white line — the intersection almost solves itself. If you arrive without an answer, you''re guessing. And guessing at 35 miles per hour is how mistakes turn into crashes.

Here''s the mindset to carry forward. Think of right-of-way less like a rulebook, and more like good manners with serious stakes. You give space. You take turns. You watch out for people who can''t protect themselves. The driver who treats every intersection as a small negotiation — not a contest — is the driver who gets through a lifetime of driving without hurting anyone.' WHERE id = 'lesson_right-of-way_what-right-of-way-really-means';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'A controlled intersection is one where signs or signals tell drivers what to do. Most of the intersections you''ll meet in town are controlled. The good news — the rules are clear. The bad news — many crashes happen here because drivers stop paying attention to what the signs and signals actually require.

Let''s start with stop signs. A stop sign means a full stop. Every time. Even if you can see the intersection is empty. A full stop means the wheels stop turning. A rolling stop is not a stop. And it''s one of the most common ways new drivers get into low-speed crashes and tickets.

At a stop sign — stop at the white stop line if there is one. If not, stop before the crosswalk. If there''s no crosswalk, stop where you can see cross traffic.

After stopping — yield to any pedestrians in or entering the crosswalk. Yield to any vehicle that is close enough on the cross street to be a hazard. Then proceed when it''s safe.

Here''s a detail people forget. If you stop behind a car at a stop sign — you are not done. When that car moves, you pull up to the line and stop again. The sign controls each driver individually.

All-way stops — sometimes called four-way stops — have their own order. At an all-way stop, every approach has a stop sign. The basic order goes like this.

First to fully stop is first to go.

If two drivers stop at the same time — the driver on the right goes first.

If you are turning left and a car across from you is going straight or turning right — they go first.

The most useful skill at a four-way stop is patience plus eye contact. If everyone is being polite at once — gently take your turn when it''s clearly yours. Don''t wave others through out of order. You confuse the people behind them.

Yield signs mean slow down, be ready to stop, and let other traffic and pedestrians go first. You only stop if you have to. The key word is ready. If you fly past a yield sign without ever scanning — you''ve treated it like nothing was there.

You''ll see yield signs at freeway on-ramps, T-intersections, and entrances to roundabouts. The merge lane onto a freeway often ends in a yield sign, or a yield-style merge. The cars already on the freeway have the right-of-way. You adjust your speed to fit into the gap.

Now, traffic signals. Signals seem obvious until you have to make a judgment call. Here are the basics.

Solid red. Stop and stay stopped until green. Right turn on red is often allowed after a full stop and a yield — but only where it isn''t prohibited by a posted sign.

Solid yellow. The light is about to turn red. Stop if you can do so safely. Don''t speed up to beat it.

Solid green. Go if the intersection is clear. A green light is not a command to enter. It''s permission. If a car is still finishing their left turn — let them clear.

Flashing red. Treat it like a stop sign.

Flashing yellow. Slow down and proceed with caution.

Protected versus permitted left turns trips up new drivers constantly. Let me break it down.

A green arrow is a protected turn. Oncoming traffic has a red. You can turn without yielding to them. But you still yield to pedestrians in your crosswalk.

A solid green light, while you''re in a left-turn lane, is a permitted turn. You must yield to oncoming traffic and pedestrians. Then turn when there''s a safe gap.

A flashing yellow arrow is also permitted. You may turn — but you must yield to oncoming traffic and pedestrians.

Here''s what to do if you''re sitting in the intersection on a permitted green waiting for a gap, and the light turns yellow. Complete your turn carefully when oncoming traffic stops. Don''t panic and freeze.

There''s a concept called the dilemma zone. When a green light turns yellow — there''s a short distance where you''re not sure if you can stop in time, or should keep going. Your default should be — if you can stop safely, stop. Slamming the brakes on a wet road can be just as dangerous as running the yellow. Use your judgment based on your speed, the road surface, and the car behind you. If you decide to go — don''t speed up. Maintain your speed and clear the intersection.

Pedestrian signals matter to you too. The walk signal is for pedestrians, but it tells you a lot. A flashing don''t walk, or a countdown timer ticking down, means your green is about to end. If you''re approaching and the countdown is at 3 — you''re not making this light. Start slowing down.

Here''s the habit to build. At every controlled intersection — do a mental check. What does the control say? What does traffic actually look like? Who has not yet yielded? The sign or signal is your starting point — not your ending point. Real intersections are made of people. And people sometimes ignore the rules. Your eyes verify what the signs promise.' WHERE id = 'lesson_right-of-way_controlled-intersections-signs-and-signals';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Not every intersection has a sign or signal. In neighborhoods, parking lots, alleys, and rural areas — you''ll meet intersections where the rules are unwritten on the pavement, but very much in the law. These are uncontrolled intersections. And they cause more crashes than they should, because drivers stop expecting them.

So what does uncontrolled really mean? An uncontrolled intersection is one with no stop sign, yield sign, or signal facing your direction of travel. Sometimes one street has stop signs and the cross street doesn''t. That''s a two-way stop. Sometimes nobody has anything. Either way — the law has a default order so drivers can still figure out who goes.

Here are the core rules to memorize.

If you arrive first and the other driver hasn''t — you go first.

If you arrive at the same time — the driver on the left yields to the driver on the right.

If you are turning left — you yield to oncoming traffic going straight or turning right.

A vehicle on a paved road generally has the right-of-way over a vehicle entering from an unpaved road or driveway.

One more rule that matters in real neighborhoods. A vehicle leaving a driveway, alley, parking lot, or private road must yield to traffic and pedestrians on the public road. That includes you pulling out of your own driveway. The sidewalk crossing your driveway is still a pedestrian space.

Two-way stops are more dangerous than they look. You have stop signs. The cross street doesn''t. When you stop — you might assume any approaching car will also stop. They won''t. They may be going 45 miles per hour, and not expecting you to pull out.

At a two-way stop — stop fully. Look left, right, and left again. The car closest to you on your left is the first threat. Wait for a gap big enough not just to enter the intersection — but to fully clear it, or merge with traffic. When in doubt, wait. A few extra seconds is cheap.

T-intersections work like this. A T-intersection is where one road ends at another. If the through road — the top of the T — has no sign or signal, traffic on the through road has the right-of-way. The driver coming up the stem of the T must yield, whether or not there''s a sign. Treat the absence of a sign as a yield — not as permission to drive through.

Now, pedestrians. They are the most important yielders. A pedestrian is anyone outside a vehicle. People walking, jogging, using a wheelchair or mobility scooter. Kids on foot. Drivers must yield to pedestrians in a crosswalk. And that includes crosswalks you can''t see.

Here are key facts that surprise new drivers.

Every intersection has crosswalks — even if there are no painted lines. The lines just make it visible. The right to cross is the same.

You must yield to pedestrians who are in your half of the road. And to those approaching close enough to be in danger. You don''t get to scoot through just because they''re not directly in front of your bumper.

You may not pass a vehicle stopped at a crosswalk. If the car next to you stops for no obvious reason near an intersection — assume there''s a pedestrian you can''t see. And stop too.

Blind or low-vision pedestrians using a white cane or guide dog always have the right-of-way. Stop and wait. No matter where they are.

Kids deserve extra space. They dart. They don''t look. They may not understand that a green light for them is a permission slip — not a force field. Slow down in school zones and near parks. Even when the speed limit doesn''t drop.

Cyclists and people on scooters often have the same right-of-way as cars when they''re in the roadway. And the same right-of-way as pedestrians when they''re in a crosswalk. Rules vary — but treat them as protected users either way.

Here are common situations to watch.

Right hooks. You turn right across a cyclist going straight in a bike lane. Always check your right blind spot and mirror before turning right.

Left crosses. You turn left across an oncoming cyclist. Cyclists are smaller and harder to spot. Don''t assume the road is clear just because you don''t see a car.

The door zone. If you''re driving next to parked cars — leave room for a door to open, or a cyclist to swerve.

Emergency and special vehicles get special treatment. When you see or hear an emergency vehicle with lights and sirens — pull to the right edge of the road when safe, and stop. Don''t stop in an intersection. Clear it first, then pull over. Wait until they pass — and any others behind them pass. Don''t follow within 500 feet. That''s about 1.5 football fields.

For a stopped emergency vehicle, tow truck, or roadside worker with flashing lights — move over a lane if you can. Or slow down significantly if you can''t. This is sometimes called a move-over duty. It exists because people working on the shoulder die every year, from drivers who didn''t give them space.

School buses are non-negotiable. When a school bus stops with its red lights flashing and stop arm out — traffic in both directions usually has to stop. Unless you are on the opposite side of a divided road with a physical barrier. The kids walk in front of the bus, where you can''t see them. Treat the flashing red lights as a non-negotiable full stop.

Here''s the habit that keeps you safe. Uncontrolled intersections punish autopilot. The fix is simple. Every time the pavement changes. Every time you enter a neighborhood. Every time you leave a driveway — ask, who else might be here, and who is supposed to yield? If the answer is me — then yield like you mean it.' WHERE id = 'lesson_right-of-way_uncontrolled-intersections-and-pedestrians';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Some right-of-way situations don''t fit the simple who''s on the right rules. Roundabouts, freeway merges, lane changes, and roadway hazards all have their own logic. They feel intimidating at first because there''s motion in every direction. But each one is built on the same idea — traffic already in motion has priority over traffic trying to enter.

Let''s talk roundabouts. A roundabout is a circular intersection where traffic flows counter-clockwise — in countries that drive on the right. Roundabouts are safer than traditional intersections, because they remove the chance of a high-speed broadside crash. Everyone is moving the same direction, at low speed.

The rules are simpler than they look.

Slow down as you approach. Most roundabouts are designed for 15 to 25 miles per hour inside the circle.

Yield to traffic already in the roundabout. They have the right-of-way. You enter on a gap.

Yield to pedestrians in the crosswalks at the entrance and exit.

Do not stop inside the roundabout. Once you''re in, keep moving. Stopping causes rear-end crashes.

Use your right turn signal as you approach your exit — not when you enter. The signal tells drivers waiting to enter that you''re leaving.

Multi-lane roundabouts add one more skill. Picking the right lane before you enter. Generally — the right lane is for the first exit, the right turn, or going straight. The left lane is for going straight, left turns, or U-turns.

Watch for the lane-use signs and pavement arrows before the roundabout. Pick your lane early. Once you''re inside — do not change lanes. If you miss your exit — just go around again. Looping is free. Cutting across lanes is dangerous.

What about emergency vehicles in roundabouts? If an emergency vehicle is approaching — do not stop in the circle. Exit first. Then pull over to let them through.

Freeway and highway merges are next. Merging is a place where being timid is as dangerous as being aggressive. The basic rule is — traffic on the freeway has the right-of-way. Merging traffic must adjust speed and find a gap.

Good merging is a three-step move.

First, on the on-ramp — accelerate to roughly the speed of traffic. Crawling onto a freeway at 35 miles per hour, when traffic is moving at 65 miles per hour, is a setup for a crash.

Second, in the merge lane — look over your left shoulder and into your mirror. Find a gap. And signal.

Third — merge smoothly into the gap, without forcing other drivers to slam on their brakes.

Drivers already on the freeway should move over a lane when possible to make room. But they aren''t required to. If they don''t, you have to fit. Speed up or slow down to find a gap. Do not stop in the merge lane, unless traffic is fully stopped.

Now, the zipper merge. When a lane is closing ahead — construction, a crash — the safest approach is the zipper merge. Use both lanes until the merge point. Then alternate, one car from each lane. It feels rude to use the closing lane all the way to the front. But research shows it actually cuts backup length by up to 40%. Let people in. Don''t ride bumpers to block them.

Lane changes within traffic are a small right-of-way negotiation. The cars in the lane you want to enter have the right-of-way. You must signal before you move — not while you move. Check your mirror and your blind spot. Find a gap and slide into it, without making anyone else brake.

If the car in the next lane speeds up when you signal — don''t fight them. Drop back and try again. Most road rage incidents start with a lane change someone took without asking.

Funerals and processions get their own rule. A funeral procession is a line of vehicles, usually with headlights on and hazard lights flashing, following a lead vehicle. In most places, the procession is treated as a single unit. Once the lead car legally enters an intersection — the rest can follow, even on a red light. As another driver — you yield to the procession, and do not cut into it.

In work zones and incident scenes — the normal rules can be overridden by temporary signs. Lower speed limits. Lane closures. Flaggers with signs or flags. A flagger''s directions outrank a traffic signal. And pilot vehicles guiding you through one-way sections.

Obey the flagger. Slow down. Fines are usually doubled. But more importantly — workers are inches from traffic.

Trains and railroad crossings always have the right-of-way. They cannot stop quickly. At a crossing — stop if lights are flashing, gates are down, or a train is close enough to be a hazard. Even without active signals.

Never try to beat a train. Trains are bigger and closer than they look. And they are moving faster than they appear. Don''t stop on the tracks in traffic. Make sure there''s room on the far side before you cross.

Animals and unusual obstacles come up in some areas. Livestock being herded on a roadway have the right-of-way. So do horses being ridden. Pass them slowly, and give wide space, because horses can spook. Wildlife doesn''t follow rules at all. In areas with deer, moose, or elk — slow down at dawn and dusk. And remember — if you see one animal, more are likely nearby.

Notice the pattern across all these situations. The people or vehicles already moving, already in the lane, already on the track, already in the circle — have the priority. Your job as the entering driver is to fit in safely. Once you internalize that — the special situations stop being special. They''re just one rule, applied to a hundred different intersections.' WHERE id = 'lesson_right-of-way_roundabouts-merges-and-special-situations';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Most crashes are not caused by bad luck. They are caused by drivers who saw the problem too late — or never saw it at all. Scanning is the habit of constantly moving your eyes to gather information. About what is around you. What is changing. And what could go wrong in the next few seconds.

When you scan well, you get something incredibly valuable — time. Time to lift off the gas. Time to cover the brake. Time to pick an escape path. A driver who sees a hazard two seconds earlier than another driver has roughly twice as long to respond. That difference is often the difference between a near miss and a crash.

Here''s the thing — the brain can only react to what the eyes notice. Your car does exactly what you tell it to do. But you can only tell it the right thing if your eyes have already given your brain the right information.

New drivers tend to make two classic mistakes. They lock their eyes on one spot — usually the car directly in front of them. Or they look down at the road, just past the hood of their own car.

Both habits shrink the world down to a tiny bubble. Inside that bubble — you are always reacting to surprises. Because everything outside it is invisible, until it suddenly enters.

Scanning is active. Not passive. Looking is not the same as seeing. You can stare straight ahead for a full minute, and still miss a pedestrian stepping off a curb, if your brain was somewhere else.

Active scanning means deliberately asking questions as your eyes move. What is the car ahead doing? Speeding up, slowing down, drifting? What is happening at the next intersection? Are there brake lights three or four cars ahead? Is anything moving near the edges of the road, like a kid, a dog, or a cyclist? What is behind me? And what is in my blind spots?

You are not just collecting pretty pictures. You are building a moving map of risk.

Let''s talk about the cost of distraction. Every second your eyes are off the road — you are driving blind. At 55 miles per hour — two seconds is about 160 feet. That''s longer than half a football field. A glance at a text message. A long look at the radio. Even a stare at an interesting billboard — erases your scanning entirely. Trained drivers treat their eyes as the most important tool in the car. More important than the steering wheel itself.

Here''s what good scanning looks like. A driver with strong scanning habits does several things at once. They keep their eyes moving every couple of seconds. They look far ahead — not just at the bumper in front of them. They check mirrors regularly, not only before lane changes. They notice changes, like a brake light flicker, or a head turning in a parked car. And they plan an out — an escape route they could use if something goes wrong.

This sounds like a lot. It becomes automatic with practice — the same way you stopped having to think about tying your shoes. The goal of this module is to turn scanning into a habit you do without thinking. So your brain is free to make good decisions when something unexpected happens.

Finally — the mindset shift. Beginners think driving is about controlling the car. Experienced safe drivers know driving is mostly about managing information. The pedals and the wheel are easy. The hard part — and the part that keeps you alive — is seeing the world clearly, and early. Everything else in this module builds on that one idea.' WHERE id = 'lesson_scanning-and-hazard-perception_why-scanning-matters';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Good scanning is not random. Safe drivers follow a repeatable pattern that sweeps their eyes across the road in a predictable way. A search pattern keeps you from getting tunnel vision. And makes sure no part of your environment goes unchecked for too long.

The basic rule is — look high, look wide, look often. Three simple rules guide every search pattern.

High. Look far down the road. Not just at the car in front of you.

Wide. Sweep your eyes across the full width of the scene — including sidewalks, shoulders, and side streets.

Often. Keep your eyes moving. No single spot deserves a long stare.

A useful rough target is to move your eyes to a new area about every two seconds. You are not racing your eyeballs around. You are flowing from one zone to the next.

Now, the 12 to 15 second view. Look as far ahead as you can see clearly — roughly where you will be in 12 to 15 seconds. In the city — that might be the next block. On a highway — it might be a quarter mile or more.

Why so far? You will spot brake lights, slow traffic, or lane closures before they are a problem. You will see traffic lights early enough to decide whether you can stop comfortably. And you will notice the overall flow of traffic — not just one car.

After looking far — bring your eyes back through the middle distance. That''s about 4 to 8 seconds ahead. Then close to your car. Then back out again. Think of it as a loop. Not a stare.

Use the edges of the road. Hazards rarely appear in the middle of your lane out of nowhere. They come from the sides. A parked car door. A pedestrian stepping off a curb. A dog running out from a yard. A car easing out of a driveway. Train your eyes to check the edges. Not just the center.

At intersections — look left, then right, then left again before you go. The reason for the second left look is that the closest threat to you comes from the left in many traffic patterns. And the situation can change in the seconds it took you to look right.

Mirrors are part of the pattern. Mirrors are not just for lane changes. A common rule of thumb is to glance at a mirror every 5 to 8 seconds. You are checking — is anyone closing fast behind you? Is a vehicle in your blind spot? Did the car behind you just brake hard, suggesting a chain of events you should know about?

Knowing what is behind you matters. Because your best escape from a hazard ahead might be braking hard. And that only works if no one is tailgating you.

Blind spot checks come next. Mirrors do not show everything. Before any lane change, merge, or turn — do a quick head turn to check the blind spot on the side you are moving toward. This is a fast glance. Not a long stare. Your eyes should be back on the road ahead within a second.

Here''s a sample search loop. A practical pattern looks like this — repeated continuously.

Far ahead. Where will I be in 12 to 15 seconds?

Middle distance. What is the car a few ahead doing?

Just in front. The gap to the car immediately ahead.

Sides and edges. Sidewalks, driveways, side streets.

Mirror. Rear first. Then the side mirror that matters most for your situation.

Then repeat.

At first, this feels like a checklist. With practice — it becomes a smooth, almost unconscious flow. The goal is for your eyes to never settle anywhere long enough to miss what is happening somewhere else.

Finally — avoid the freeway stare. Long, straight highways are deceptively dangerous, because the scene barely changes. Drivers fall into a stare where the car ahead becomes the whole world. Fight it by deliberately moving your eyes. Checking mirrors on a schedule. And looking at distant landmarks. Boredom is when scanning matters most.' WHERE id = 'lesson_scanning-and-hazard-perception_the-search-pattern';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Scanning tells you where to look. Hazard perception tells you what to look for. A hazard is anything that could force you to change speed or direction — or that could become dangerous if conditions shift. The earlier you spot one, the more options you have.

It helps to sort what you see into three buckets. Most driving threats fall into one of them.

First — other road users. Cars, trucks, motorcycles, cyclists, pedestrians, scooter riders, kids on bikes.

Second — the road and environment. Potholes, lane closures, debris, standing water, ice patches, sharp curves, glare from the sun.

Third — your own vehicle and state. Worn tires, low washer fluid, fatigue, frustration, distraction.

Good drivers are constantly assessing all three. A perfect driver in a poorly maintained car is still in danger. And so is a sharp car driven by someone who is exhausted.

Here''s the core skill of hazard perception. It''s prediction. When you see something, ask yourself — what could this become in the next few seconds?

A ball rolls into the street. A child may chase it.

Brake lights flash three cars ahead. Traffic may stop suddenly.

A parked car has its wheels turned out. It may pull into your lane.

A driver beside you keeps drifting toward your lane line. They may be distracted.

A pedestrian at the curb is looking at their phone. They may step out without checking.

None of these are emergencies yet. That''s exactly the point. You spot them before they become emergencies. And you adjust early — ease off the gas, cover the brake, change your lane position, or simply increase your following distance.

Small details often tell you what''s about to happen.

Brake lights and turn signals further ahead in traffic warn you of slowdowns and lane changes before they reach you.

Tire angles on parked or stopped cars suggest the direction they might move.

Head and eye movement of pedestrians and other drivers reveal their intentions.

Shadows under parked cars can hint at a person standing on the far side.

Bouncing brake lights of a car ahead can mean the driver is panicking — or the road surface is uneven.

You don''t need to consciously list these. With practice, your brain learns to flag them automatically — the way it flags a friend''s face in a crowd.

The worst hazards are the ones you can''t fully see. Hidden hazards.

A view blocked by a large vehicle, especially at intersections.

A blind curve where the road disappears around a bend.

A hilltop where you can''t see what''s on the other side.

A truck stopped at a crosswalk, which may hide a pedestrian walking across.

A driveway or alley between buildings.

When your view is blocked — assume the worst. Slow down. Be ready for something to step, roll, or pull out from behind whatever is in the way. The professional saying is — if you can''t see, don''t go.

The environment itself is a hazard you must read.

Wet roads after a dry spell are slipperiest in the first few minutes — before rain washes oil off the surface.

Bright sun low in the sky can blind both you and other drivers, especially at sunrise and sunset.

Fog, snow, and heavy rain shrink your scanning distance. So you must slow down to match what you can actually see.

Cold mornings can leave invisible ice patches on bridges and shaded curves.

If conditions cut your visibility in half, your speed should usually come down too. The rule is simple. Never drive faster than you can see.

A powerful mental habit is constant what-if thinking. What if that car pulls out? What if this light turns yellow? What if the truck ahead brakes hard? You''re not being paranoid. You''re running quick simulations — so that when something does happen, your brain has already rehearsed a response. And you act in a fraction of a second instead of freezing.' WHERE id = 'lesson_scanning-and-hazard-perception_identifying-hazards-early';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Spotting hazards early only helps if you have room to do something about them. Space is your safety margin. The more space you keep around your car — the more time you have to scan, decide, and act. Hazard perception and space management are two halves of the same skill.

Imagine an invisible bubble surrounding your vehicle on all four sides. Your job is to keep that bubble as big as conditions allow. When traffic squeezes the bubble, your risk goes up. When you create space, your risk goes down.

There are four zones to manage. Front — the gap between you and the car ahead. Rear — the gap behind you, including any tailgaters. And left and right — the space beside you, especially in adjacent lanes.

You can''t always control all four. But you can almost always influence at least one — by adjusting your speed or lane position.

Now, following distance. The 3-second minimum. The most important space is in front of you, because that''s where most collisions happen.

Here''s a simple way to check your following distance. Pick a fixed object ahead — like a sign or a crack in the road. When the car in front of you passes it, count. One one-thousand, two one-thousand, three one-thousand. If you reach the same object before you finish counting, you''re too close.

3 seconds is a minimum for dry, clear conditions. Increase it to 4 or more seconds when the road is wet, snowy, or icy. When visibility is poor. When you''re following a motorcycle, a large truck, or a vehicle whose brake lights you can''t see. When you''re tired or driving an unfamiliar car. And when someone is tailgating you. Yes — more space, not less.

It sounds backwards, but if someone is riding your bumper, you should leave more room in front, not less. The extra cushion means you can brake gradually instead of slamming the brakes — which reduces the chance the tailgater rear-ends you. Never brake-check someone. It can cause a serious crash.

Now let''s talk about the sides. You often have a choice of where to position your car within your lane. Use it. If a row of parked cars is on your right, drift slightly toward the left side of your lane to add space in case a door opens. If a large truck is beside you, ease away from it. The goal is to avoid being boxed in with no escape route.

Here''s a useful rule. Try not to drive directly beside another vehicle for long. Either pass it cleanly or drop back so you have room to maneuver. Sitting in someone''s blind spot is one of the most dangerous places on the road.

Keep an escape route. For every situation, ask yourself — if something bad happened right now, where would I go?

A shoulder or breakdown lane.

An open lane next to you.

A gap behind you, which you can use by braking.

A driveway or open parking area.

Good drivers constantly update this mental escape plan. It changes every few seconds as traffic moves. You may go an entire trip without ever using one. But the day you need it — having thought about it first is what saves you.

Speed is part of space. Speed and space are linked. The faster you go, the more distance you cover per second, and the more space you need ahead of you. Stopping distances grow much faster than speed. Doubling your speed can roughly quadruple your stopping distance — because both your reaction distance and your braking distance grow.

This is why slowing down in bad conditions isn''t just polite. It''s the only way to keep your safety bubble the right size. If you can''t see far, you can''t stop in time at high speed.

Now, bringing it all together. Scanning, hazard perception, and space management work as one system. You scan with a deliberate pattern. You spot small clues and predict what they might become. And you keep enough space and an escape route so you can act in time.

Do all three — and you become the kind of driver who almost never gets surprised. The crashes that strike other drivers as sudden are the ones you saw coming and quietly avoided ten seconds earlier. That''s the whole goal of this module. And the foundation of every other driving skill you will learn.' WHERE id = 'lesson_scanning-and-hazard-perception_managing-space-and-time';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'The posted speed limit is a ceiling — not a target. It tells you the fastest a normal driver can usually go on that road in good conditions. Your job is to pick a speed that fits what''s actually happening right now. The weather. The traffic. The road surface. Your visibility. And your own experience.

A 45 miles per hour sign on a sunny, empty road means 45 is probably fine. The same sign in heavy rain, at night, with a line of brake lights ahead — means 45 is too fast.

Almost every state has a law that says you must drive at a speed that is reasonable for current conditions — even if that''s well below the posted limit. Getting rear-ended is bad. Rear-ending someone because you couldn''t stop in time is worse. And it''s almost always considered your fault.

Now, what changes your safe speed? Think of these as dials that turn your safe speed down.

Weather. Rain, snow, fog, and ice all reduce tire grip and visibility. Wet roads can double your stopping distance. Ice can multiply it many times over.

Light. At night you can only see as far as your headlights reach. If you''re driving faster than you can stop within that lit zone — you''re overdriving your headlights.

Traffic density. More cars means less room to react. Cars merging, braking, or changing lanes shrink the space you have to work with.

Road type and surface. Gravel, potholes, construction zones, and sharp curves all demand a slower speed than smooth straight pavement.

Your experience. A new driver needs more time to process what''s happening. Going a little slower buys you that time.

Here''s the physics you can''t argue with. Speed doesn''t add risk in a straight line. It multiplies it. The energy your car carries grows with the square of its speed. Doubling your speed from 30 to 60 miles per hour quadruples the energy that has to be absorbed in a crash. That''s why a small bump in speed can turn a fender bender into a serious injury.

Stopping distance has two parts.

Reaction distance — how far you travel while your brain notices a problem and your foot moves to the brake. About three quarters of a second for an alert driver. Longer if you''re tired or distracted.

Braking distance — how far you travel once the brakes are doing their work. This grows quickly with speed and with worse road conditions.

At 30 miles per hour on dry pavement, a typical car needs roughly 90 feet to stop from the moment you spot a hazard. At 60 miles per hour, it''s closer to 300 feet — more than the length of a football field.

Now, going with the flow. Driving much slower than the cars around you isn''t automatically safe. Big speed differences cause crashes too. Other drivers will brake hard behind you, swerve around you, or tailgate. On most roads the safest place is moving at about the same speed as surrounding traffic — as long as that speed is legal and reasonable for conditions. If everyone is going 10 over and the road is icy, the answer isn''t to match them. The answer is to slow down, move right, and let them pass.

A few quick habits to build.

Glance at your speedometer every 5 to 10 seconds, especially after a turn or coming off a ramp.

When conditions get worse, take your foot off the gas before you think about the brake. Coasting down is smoother and safer than stabbing the pedal.

On unfamiliar roads — assume the next curve is sharper than it looks until you can see through it.

And if something feels too fast — it is. Trust that signal and ease off.' WHERE id = 'lesson_speed-and-space-management_choosing-a-safe-speed';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Good drivers think about space the way a goalie thinks about angles. Your car sits inside a bubble of empty space — and you want to keep that bubble as big as you can on every side. Space gives you time. Time gives you options. Options keep you out of crashes.

Picture your car at the center of a tic-tac-toe grid. There are six zones that matter.

Front — the most important zone. Almost everything you have to react to comes from in front of you.

Rear — the zone you control the least. You manage it by braking smoothly and giving warning with your brake lights.

Left side and right side — the lanes or shoulders next to you. These are your escape routes.

And front-left and front-right — the diagonal areas where cars merge into your path or pull out from driveways.

When all six zones are open, you have full flexibility. When one or more closes, your options shrink. And risk goes up.

Now, the front zone. Following distance. The front zone is non-negotiable. If you have no space in front of you, no other zone can save you.

Use the three-second rule in good conditions. First — pick a fixed point ahead, like a sign or a shadow on the road. Second — when the car ahead passes it, count. One-thousand-one, one-thousand-two, one-thousand-three. Third — if you reach the point before you finish counting, you''re too close. Ease off.

3 seconds is the floor — not a goal. Add at least one second for each of these.

Rain or wet pavement.

Snow, ice, or slush. Add several seconds.

Night driving.

Towing or being heavily loaded.

Driving a vehicle you aren''t used to.

Following a motorcycle. They can stop very quickly.

Or a driver ahead who seems distracted or unpredictable.

In heavy rain or snow, 4 to 6 seconds is reasonable. On ice — even more.

Now the rear zone. Managing tailgaters. You can''t force a tailgater to back off. But you can lower the risk.

Increase your front gap. This sounds backwards, but it works. With more space ahead, you can slow down gradually instead of hitting the brakes hard. That keeps the tailgater from rear-ending you.

Move over. If there''s a right lane available, use it and let them pass.

And don''t brake-check. Tapping the brakes to teach a lesson is how chain-reaction crashes start.

Now the side zones. Keep escape routes open. Try not to drive in clusters. When you''re surrounded by cars on every side, a single mistake by any driver in the pack can trap you. If a group of cars catches up to you, adjust your speed slightly to drift out of the cluster. A few seconds of patience can leave you alone on an open stretch of road with options in every direction.

Avoid riding next to large trucks for long stretches. Their blind spots are huge. And you have no easy escape if they drift into your lane.

Here''s why space is more powerful than reflexes. A new driver might assume that good reflexes can make up for tight following distances. They can''t. Reaction time is mostly fixed by biology — around three quarters of a second for an alert person. Space, on the other hand, is something you can adjust at any moment with your right foot. You can buy yourself another second of reaction time just by lifting off the gas. That''s an enormous safety upgrade — for almost no effort.

Putting it together. Every few seconds, do a quick mental check. Front, rear, left, right. Are all four open? If one is closed, can you open it by changing speed or lane position? Drivers who do this constantly look calm and smooth from the outside. They aren''t lucky. They''re just keeping their bubble inflated.' WHERE id = 'lesson_speed-and-space-management_the-space-bubble-around-your-car';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Traffic isn''t random. It moves in patterns. And good drivers learn to read those patterns — so they''re reacting to what''s about to happen, not what already happened. This is the difference between driving and just steering.

Look far ahead. New drivers tend to stare at the back bumper of the car in front of them. That gives them only a second or two of warning when something goes wrong. Experienced drivers look much farther down the road — usually 12 to 15 seconds ahead. On a city street that''s about a block. On a highway it can be a quarter mile or more.

Looking far ahead helps you see brake lights before the car right in front of you reacts. It helps you spot lane closures, debris, or stalled cars while you still have time to change lanes calmly. It helps you notice changes in road surface or weather before you hit them. And it helps you predict when a light will change — so you can ease off the gas instead of slamming the brakes.

Your eyes lead. Your hands and feet follow. If you keep your eyes pointed only at the next car, you''ll always be late.

Scan — don''t stare. Good drivers move their eyes in a pattern. About every two seconds, sweep.

Far ahead.

Just in front of your car.

Both side mirrors.

The rearview mirror.

And your speedometer.

This isn''t slow or distracting once it becomes a habit. It takes only a second or two — and keeps a full picture of traffic in your head at all times.

Now, reading other drivers. Cars give away their intentions in dozens of small ways.

Brake lights down the line. A wave of brake lights three or four cars ahead means traffic is slowing. Lift off the gas now.

Drift within a lane. A driver weaving slightly may be distracted, tired, or impaired. Give them extra space.

Turned front wheels. A car parked on the side with its wheels turned toward the road is about to pull out. Same goes for cars at a stop sign.

Slow rolling at intersections. A driver who isn''t fully stopping is one who might not yield.

Mismatched turn signals. A signal that has been on for a long time without a turn may have been left on by accident. Or the driver may turn unexpectedly. Either way — don''t bet on it.

Head movement. If you can see a driver checking their mirror or looking over their shoulder, they''re probably about to change lanes.

Reading the road itself. The road tells you what''s coming if you pay attention.

Brake light patterns at the same spot every day mean a known slowdown — like a merge or a tricky intersection.

Skid marks or dark patches suggest a place where cars often lose traction.

Glare on the pavement after rain can hide standing water and slick patches.

Shaded curves in cold weather hold ice longer than sunny ones.

And trash, branches, or sand on the shoulder can mean a recent crash or a debris field worth slowing for.

Anticipate the bottleneck. Traffic jams often form at predictable places. On-ramps. Lane drops. Hills where slow trucks pile up. And intersections with short green lights. When you see one coming — don''t wait until you''re stuck in it. Slow down gradually, leave extra space, and look for a lane that''s moving better. Smooth driving in heavy traffic is almost entirely about anticipating the next slowdown — instead of reacting to it.

Now, make your own intentions clear. Reading traffic is a two-way street. Other drivers are trying to read you too. Help them.

Signal at least a few seconds before you turn or change lanes — not as you do it.

Position your car clearly in a lane, not straddling the line.

Use steady speeds. Sudden bursts and brakes are hard for others to predict.

Make eye contact at four-way stops and crosswalks when you can.

When every driver around you can guess what you''ll do next — the whole system gets safer.' WHERE id = 'lesson_speed-and-space-management_reading-traffic-flow';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Everything you''ve learned about safe speed and space cushions still applies in bad weather and tricky environments. The difference is that the numbers change. You need more space, more time, and more attention. And you need to slow down before things go wrong — not after.

Rain. The most dangerous time in the rain is often the first 10 to 15 minutes. Oil, dust, and rubber that have built up on the road float to the surface and make pavement unusually slick. After a heavy rain has been falling for a while, the road actually grips better — because the surface has been rinsed off.

Adjustments for rain. Increase following distance to at least 4 seconds — more in heavy rain. Turn on your headlights. In most places this is required any time your wipers are on. Slow down before puddles. Hitting standing water at speed can cause hydroplaning — where your tires ride on top of the water and lose grip.

If you hydroplane — don''t brake hard or jerk the wheel. Ease off the gas. Keep the wheel pointed straight. And wait for the tires to grip again.

Now, snow and ice. Snow and ice cut your traction dramatically. On packed snow you may have less than half the grip of dry pavement. On ice it can drop to almost nothing.

Adjustments for snow and ice. Increase following distance to 6 seconds or more. On ice, leave even more. Accelerate gently. Mashing the gas just spins the tires and loses traction. Brake early and softly. Sudden braking causes skids.

Watch for black ice — a thin clear coating that looks like wet pavement. It''s most common on bridges, overpasses, shaded curves, and the first cold mornings of the season.

If you start to skid — look and steer where you want to go. Yanking the wheel the wrong way makes the skid worse.

Fog. Fog reduces visibility — sometimes to a few car lengths. Your safe speed in fog is whatever lets you stop within the distance you can see.

Use low beams. Not high beams. High beams reflect off the fog and make it harder to see. Use fog lights if your car has them. Increase following distance, because you have less warning of slowdowns.

If fog gets too thick to drive safely — pull completely off the road into a parking lot or rest area. Not just onto the shoulder. Cars parked on the shoulder in fog get hit.

Night. At night your useful vision shrinks to the area lit by your headlights. Your depth perception and color recognition both get worse.

Slow down so you can stop within the distance your headlights light up. Use high beams on dark roads when there''s no oncoming traffic and no car close ahead of you. Switch to low beams when other drivers are nearby. Watch for animals at the edges of the road. Eyes reflecting your headlights are a clear warning. Keep your windshield clean inside and out. A smeared windshield turns oncoming headlights into a blinding glare.

Heavy traffic and stop-and-go. In slow, dense traffic the biggest risks are rear-end crashes and lane-change crashes. Tight space and constant speed changes punish anyone who isn''t paying attention.

Keep at least one full car length of space ahead, even when stopped. This gives you somewhere to go if you''re about to be rear-ended. And it lets you pull out if the car ahead breaks down. Avoid changing lanes constantly to chase the faster lane. You rarely save real time — and every lane change adds risk. Stay off your phone. Crawling traffic is the easiest place to drift into the car in front of you.

Construction zones. Work zones combine narrower lanes, uneven surfaces, sudden speed drops, and workers near traffic. Fines are usually higher here for a reason.

Slow down well before the cones start — not at the last second. Merge early when a lane is closing ahead. Late merges create dangerous bottlenecks. Increase following distance. Workers, equipment, or pavement changes can force the car ahead to brake hard. And never assume a work zone is empty just because you don''t see workers right at that moment.

Here''s the one rule that ties it all together. When conditions get worse, two things must change. Your speed comes down. And your space cushion goes up. Drivers who get into trouble in bad weather are almost always the ones who tried to keep driving the way they would on a clear summer afternoon. Adjust early. Adjust visibly. And you''ll handle conditions that send other drivers into the ditch.' WHERE id = 'lesson_speed-and-space-management_speed-and-space-in-tough-conditions';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Driving at night isn''t just daytime driving with the lights on. Your eyes work differently in the dark. The road gives you less information. And the drivers around you are more likely to be tired or impaired. Most new drivers underestimate how much changes the moment the sun goes down.

Your eyes lose superpowers after dark. In daylight, your eyes pick up sharp detail, true colors, and accurate distances. After sunset, three things drop fast.

Visual acuity. You can''t read signs or spot hazards as far away. A pedestrian in dark clothing might not be visible until you''re 50 feet from them — even with headlights.

Depth perception. Judging how far away a car is, or how fast it''s closing on you, gets harder. Two headlights in the distance can look closer or farther than they really are.

Color vision. Reds and other warm colors fade first. Brake lights still work, but subtle color cues — like a yellow caution sign in a shadow — are weaker.

Your eyes also need time to adjust. Walking from a bright room into a dark yard, you can''t see for a few seconds. The same thing happens when you leave a well-lit parking lot or pass under bright stadium lights. Plan for that adjustment — instead of being surprised by it.

You see less of the road. Low-beam headlights typically light up the road about 150 to 250 feet ahead. High beams reach roughly 350 to 500 feet. That sounds like a lot. But at highway speeds you cover that distance in just a few seconds. If something appears at the edge of your headlights, you have very little time to react.

This creates a rule of thumb worth memorizing. Don''t outdrive your headlights. Your stopping distance should fit inside the area your headlights light up. If you can''t stop within what you can see — you''re going too fast for the conditions, even if you''re under the speed limit.

Other drivers are riskier at night. The road population changes after dark.

More drivers are tired, especially after 10 p.m. and in the early morning hours.

More drivers have been drinking or using other substances. Fatal crashes per mile driven are several times higher at night than during the day.

Pedestrians and cyclists are harder to see — and may be wearing dark clothing.

Animals are more active at dawn and dusk. And many are most active at night.

You can''t control any of that. But you can assume it. Drive like the car coming the other way might drift. And like something might step out from the shoulder. That mindset isn''t paranoid. It''s realistic.

Glare is a real hazard — not an annoyance. Bright lights at night briefly blind you. After staring into oncoming high beams, your eyes can take several seconds to recover. During those seconds, you''re effectively driving without seeing.

To reduce glare — keep your windshield clean inside and out. A film of grime scatters light and makes glare worse. Dim your dashboard lights. A bright dash makes the road outside look darker. Don''t stare at oncoming headlights. Look toward the right edge of your lane and use it to guide you until the car passes. Use the night setting on your rearview mirror, or tilt the lever, to cut glare from cars behind you.

Fatigue sneaks up on you. Your body wants to sleep when it''s dark. Even if you feel fine at the start of a drive, drowsiness builds. Warning signs include heavy eyelids, drifting in your lane, missing exits, or not remembering the last few miles. If any of that happens — pull over somewhere safe and rest. Switch drivers. Or end the trip. Caffeine and loud music are temporary tricks. Not solutions.

Here''s the takeaway. Night driving asks more from you than day driving. More focus. More space. More humility about what you can and can''t see. The drivers who handle it well are the ones who slow down a little, look farther ahead, and stop trusting that everyone else is paying attention.' WHERE id = 'lesson_night-driving_why-night-driving-is-harder';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Your headlights do two jobs. They let you see. And they let other people see you. Most new drivers focus on the first job and forget about the second. Knowing which lights to use, and when — is one of the simplest skills that separates a confident night driver from a dangerous one.

Headlights on means visible. A huge share of vehicles are hit at dusk because the driver waited too long to turn on their lights. By the time you notice it''s hard to see — other drivers have already had trouble seeing you for several minutes.

A few good habits. Turn on your headlights as soon as the sun starts to set — not when it''s fully dark. Turn them on in rain, fog, snow, or any time visibility drops. Turn them on at dawn until full daylight. And if your wipers are on, your headlights should be on too. Many places make this a law. But the safety reason is the same everywhere.

Daytime running lights aren''t enough at night. They light up the front of your car but usually leave the tail lights dark. From behind — you look like a parked car.

Low beams. Your default. Low beams are aimed down and to the right so they light up the road in front of you without blinding oncoming drivers. They''re your default setting for almost every situation. City streets. Suburban roads. Highways with traffic. And anywhere there are streetlights.

Low beams reach about 150 to 250 feet ahead. That''s enough for moderate speeds — but not for high speeds on a dark road.

High beams. Powerful but social. High beams roughly double how far you can see, reaching 350 to 500 feet ahead. They''re meant for dark, open roads where you need that extra range.

Use high beams when you''re on a rural or unlit road with no cars in front of you or coming toward you. Or when you''re driving fast enough that low beams don''t give you enough warning.

Switch back to low beams when a car is coming toward you, usually within about 500 feet — when you can clearly see headlights approaching. When you''re following another car within about 200 to 300 feet. High beams shine straight into their mirrors and blind them. And when you enter a lit area, fog, heavy rain, or snow.

In fog, rain, or snow — high beams actually make things worse. The light bounces off the water or snow in the air and reflects back at you, creating a wall of glare. Low beams cut through better.

If an oncoming driver leaves their high beams on — don''t flash yours back as revenge. You''ll just blind each other. Look toward the right edge of your lane and let them pass.

Fog lights and auxiliary lights. Some cars have separate fog lights mounted low on the front bumper. They''re aimed low and wide to light up the road surface without reflecting off fog. Use them only in real low-visibility weather — and turn them off afterward. Running fog lights on a clear night is rude. And it can be illegal in many places, because they dazzle other drivers.

Don''t forget the lights you don''t see. Walk around your car once a week with the lights on and check that everything works.

Headlights — both low and high beam.

Tail lights.

Brake lights. Have someone watch while you press the pedal.

Turn signals — front and back.

Reverse lights.

License plate light.

A burned-out tail light is invisible to you while you''re driving. But it''s a real reason cars get rear-ended at night. Replace bulbs as soon as you notice them out.

Keep your headlight lenses clean. Plastic lenses fog and yellow over time, which can cut your light output in half. A simple restoration kit or a wipe-down helps a lot.

Inside the car matters too. Dim your dashboard. A bright dash makes the dark road look darker by contrast and tires your eyes faster. Most cars have a dimmer dial or button near the headlight controls.

Don''t drive with the dome light on. It reflects in the windshield and ruins your night vision. If a passenger needs light — pull over.

The short version. Lights on early. Low beams as your default. High beams only when you''re alone on a dark road. And never high beams in fog or close behind another car. Check your bulbs. Keep your lenses clean. Your lights are how the rest of the world finds you in the dark.' WHERE id = 'lesson_night-driving_using-your-lights';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Most night-driving crashes come down to one of two failures. The driver didn''t see something in time. Or someone else didn''t see the driver in time. This lesson is about closing both of those gaps. The tools are simple. Scan farther. Scan smarter. And make yourself easy to spot.

Scan farther ahead than you think. During the day, good drivers look 12 to 15 seconds down the road. At night, you can''t see that far. But you should still push your eyes to the very edge of your headlights and beyond. Don''t just stare at the hood.

A few useful habits. Look at the farthest spot you can see clearly — then sweep back toward your car. Watch the sides of the road, not just the center. Animals, pedestrians, and parked cars live there. Watch for movement that isn''t lit. A walker in dark clothes may be a shape that briefly blocks a streetlight or a reflective sign. And use other cars'' headlights as scouts. If you see headlights bobbing on a road ahead, the road has hills or bumps. If they swing wide — there''s a curve.

Use the corners of your eyes. There''s a small spot in the center of each eye that has the most detail but the worst night vision. The edges of your eye are better at picking up motion in low light. That''s why a faint star can look brighter when you don''t look straight at it.

For driving — this means don''t lock your eyes on one point. Keep them moving. If you sense something at the edge of your vision, don''t dismiss it. Glance at it, and then glance back to the road. Slight side-to-side scanning helps your eyes pick up motion you''d miss with a fixed stare.

Spotting pedestrians and cyclists. This is one of the deadliest gaps at night. A person in dark clothes on an unlit road can be effectively invisible — until you''re very close.

Look for these clues. A small bobbing reflection that might be a pedal reflector, a shoe stripe, or a backpack tag. Eyes catching your headlights. Human eyes don''t glow much, but animals'' do. A patch of road that looks slightly different from the pavement around it. And movement near crosswalks, bus stops, parked cars, and the shoulders of rural roads.

Near schools, parks, and bars — slow down and assume someone is about to step out. Don''t trust that a pedestrian sees you just because your headlights are on. They may be looking at a phone. Or be impaired.

Watch for animals. Deer and other animals are most active at dawn, dusk, and through the night. If you see one — expect more. Many animals travel in groups. And a single one crossing the road often has friends right behind it.

If an animal is in your path — brake firmly in a straight line. Don''t swerve hard to avoid it. Swerving causes serious crashes with oncoming cars, trees, or rollovers. Hitting a deer is bad. Hitting a tree at 50 miles per hour is much worse. Use your horn if you have time. A long honk can scare animals out of the road.

Make yourself easy to see. Being visible is half of safety. Your job isn''t just to see. It''s to be seen.

Lights on early — every time.

Keep tail lights, brake lights, and turn signals clean and working. Snow, mud, and dust can hide them.

Signal earlier than you would in daylight. Other drivers need more time to register what you''re doing.

Tap your brakes lightly when slowing down on a dark road, even if there''s no one behind you yet. It paints your tail lights brighter for a second.

And if you have to stop on the shoulder — turn on your hazard lights. If you have them, set out reflective triangles or flares behind your car.

Keep glass and mirrors clean. A dirty windshield in daylight is annoying. At night — every smear becomes a starburst when headlights hit it. Clean the inside of your windshield too. A thin film of oil from your dashboard builds up over time and causes most of the night glare you blame on the outside.

Check your wiper blades. Streaky wipers turn rain into a light show.

A simple mindset. At night — assume pedestrians won''t see you. Assume other drivers are tired. And assume something is about to happen in the dark gap between your headlights and the next streetlight.

That mindset will slow you down a little, make you scan a little harder, and keep your finger ready over the high-beam stalk. That''s most of the job.' WHERE id = 'lesson_night-driving_seeing-and-being-seen';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Good night driving starts before you turn the key. The trip you plan, the condition of your car, and the choices you make if something goes wrong — all matter more after dark than during the day. This lesson is about the parts of night driving that happen outside the moment-to-moment scanning.

Before you leave. A quick pre-trip routine can prevent most night emergencies.

Sleep. If you''re already tired — don''t start a long night drive. There is no fix for sleep except sleep.

Eyes. If you wear glasses or contacts, wear them. Don''t wear sunglasses at night, even if oncoming lights bother you. Tinted lenses make a dark road dangerously darker.

Fuel and charge. Start with at least half a tank or a healthy battery charge. Running out in the dark on the shoulder is a serious risk.

Phone. Charge it. Have a charger in the car. Tell someone where you''re going and when you expect to arrive on longer trips.

Lights and windows. Quick walk-around. Headlights, tail lights, blinkers, brake lights. Clean the windshield inside and out. And clear snow off the whole car if needed — not just a peephole.

Climate. Set the temperature so you stay alert. Too warm makes you sleepy. The defroster keeps the windshield clear.

Pick a smarter route. The shortest route isn''t always the best one at night.

Lit roads over dark roads — when the time difference is small. Streetlights help you see pedestrians, animals, and lane lines.

Familiar roads over unfamiliar ones. Surprises are worse at night.

Divided highways over narrow two-lane roads. Most head-on crashes happen on undivided roads. And night is when impaired drivers drift.

Avoid bar-close hours when possible. The hour or two after closing time is the most dangerous time to be on the road.

If your route includes long rural stretches — plan rest stops. Gas stations and rest areas are also your fallback for fatigue.

Adjust how you drive. Night driving is a different sport played with the same equipment.

Slow down. You don''t have to crawl. But a few miles per hour under the daytime pace gives you more time to react to what your headlights find.

Increase your following distance. A daytime 3-second gap should grow to 4 or more seconds at night. Brake lights are sometimes the only warning you get.

Look farther. Signal earlier. Brake earlier. Smooth and early beats sudden and late.

Take breaks every couple of hours on long trips. Get out of the car. Walk around. Splash water on your face.

If your car breaks down at night. A breakdown after dark is more dangerous than the same breakdown at noon. Other drivers may not see you in time.

Here are the steps. First — get off the road. Coast as far onto the shoulder as you can. Ideally past a guardrail or onto an exit ramp. The farther from the travel lanes, the better.

Second — turn on your hazard lights as soon as you slow down, so traffic behind you knows.

Third — stay in the car with seatbelts on if you''re close to traffic. Getting out and standing on the shoulder is one of the most dangerous things you can do.

Fourth — if you have reflective triangles or flares, place them behind your car only if it''s safe to walk there.

Fifth — call for help. Share your location. Modern phones can share a precise location even if you don''t know the road name.

And finally — if you must leave the car, exit on the side away from traffic.

Headlights suddenly off or dim. If your headlights die on a dark road — don''t slam the brakes. Cars behind you may not see your brake lights either. Try the high beams. Many cars run high beams on a separate circuit, so they may still work. Slow gradually, signal, and pull off the road. Turn on hazard lights, interior lights — anything that helps others see you.

If oncoming high beams blind you. This happens to everyone. The right response. Slow down. Don''t stop in the lane. Look toward the right edge of your lane, not at the lights. Once the car passes, give your eyes a few seconds to recover before you assume the road ahead is clear.

Sharing the road with bigger vehicles. Trucks, buses, and other large vehicles have huge blind spots. And those blind spots are worse at night because they rely on mirrors that catch glare. Pass them quickly when it''s safe. Don''t linger beside them. And never cut in closely in front. A loaded truck can need twice as much distance to stop as a car. And at night the driver may see your tail lights late.

The bottom line. Night driving rewards planning. A rested driver, in a clean car, with working lights, on a familiar route, who slows down a little and leaves more space — has a calm trip. A tired driver rushing on a dark backroad with one tail light out is the one in the crash report. You get to choose which driver you are — before you ever leave the driveway.' WHERE id = 'lesson_night-driving_planning-night-trips';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Rain is the most common bad-weather situation you''ll drive in. It causes more crashes than most teens expect. Water changes how your tires grip — how far your headlights reach — and how well other drivers can see you. The good news. A few simple habits handle almost every rainy drive.

Let''s start with why wet roads are dangerous. Dry pavement gives your tires solid grip. Add water — and three things happen.

Your tires have to push water out of the way to even touch the road.

Stopping distances get longer. Often by 30 percent or more.

And here''s the one that surprises people. Oil and grime that built up on the road float to the surface. That makes the first 10 to 15 minutes of rain the slipperiest part of any storm. A light drizzle on a road that hasn''t seen rain in a week can be more slippery than a steady downpour an hour later.

Now, the single biggest adjustment is speed. A safe dry-road speed is not a safe wet-road speed. Here''s a good rule. Drop about 5 to 10 miles per hour below the posted limit in steady rain — and more in heavy rain. You''re not being slow. You''re matching the road.

Also increase your following distance. In dry weather, aim for a 3-second gap to the car ahead. In rain, stretch that to at least 4 to 5 seconds. Pick a fixed point like a sign. Count when the car ahead passes it. Then see how long until you reach it.

Next, let''s talk about hydroplaning. Hydroplaning is when your tires ride up on a layer of water instead of touching the road. You lose steering and braking at the same time. It usually happens above about 35 miles per hour in standing water — or at lower speeds if your tires are worn.

If you start to hydroplane, here''s what to do. Do not slam the brakes.

Ease off the gas.

Keep the steering wheel pointed straight ahead.

Wait for the tires to reconnect. Then steer gently.

Prevent hydroplaning by avoiding puddles. Drive in the tracks left by the car ahead — that pavement is drier. And keep your tires properly inflated with good tread.

Now, seeing and being seen. Turn on your headlights any time your wipers are on. In many places it''s the law. And even where it isn''t, it makes you far more visible. Use low beams — not high beams. High beams reflect off the rain and create a wall of glare.

Keep your wipers in good shape. If they smear or chatter, replace them before the next storm, not during it. Defog your windshield using the defroster — not a sleeve, which leaves streaks.

And watch for water you can''t judge. A puddle that looks shallow can be deep enough to stall your engine — or even float a small car. Never drive through moving water across a road. Six inches of moving water can knock you off your feet. A foot can carry a car away. Turn around and find another way.

After you drive through any deep water, lightly tap your brakes a few times to dry them. Wet brake pads grab unevenly and can pull your car to one side.

Here''s a quick rainy-day checklist to keep in your head.

Headlights on with the wipers.

Speed down. Following distance up.

No cruise control. Cruise control can keep applying power when you need to be slowing down.

Both hands on the wheel. Smooth inputs only.

And if visibility drops to almost zero — pull off into a safe spot like a parking lot, not the shoulder. Then wait it out.' WHERE id = 'lesson_weather-driving_driving-in-rain';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Snow and ice are the conditions where small mistakes become big crashes. The physics are simple. Less grip means less steering — less braking — and less control. Driving well in winter is mostly about being gentle, patient, and looking far ahead.

Let''s start with prep before you go. A safe winter drive starts before you turn the key.

Clear all snow off the car. Not just a peephole on the windshield. Brush off the roof too. Snow flying off your roof can blind the driver behind you.

Clear headlights, taillights, mirrors, and the back window completely.

Check that your wipers, defroster, and heater all work before you need them.

Keep at least half a tank of gas. It helps in traffic jams and prevents fuel-line problems in cold snaps.

Carry a basic kit. Ice scraper, gloves, a blanket, a phone charger, and some snacks for long trips.

Tires matter more than anything else. If you drive often in heavy snow, dedicated winter tires grip dramatically better than all-season tires. Bald or worn tires turn even a light snow into a serious problem.

Now, driving smoothly. The golden rule on snow and ice — every input has to be smooth. Sudden gas, sudden braking, and sudden steering are the three things that break traction.

Accelerate gently. If your wheels spin, ease off until they grip.

Brake early and gradually. Look way ahead so you have time.

Steer with small movements. Big corrections cause skids.

Following distance should be much longer than usual. Try 8 to 10 seconds behind the car ahead. You''ll need it.

Let''s talk about black ice. Black ice is a thin, clear layer of ice that looks like wet pavement. It forms most often on bridges and overpasses — which freeze first because cold air surrounds them.

It also forms in shaded spots under trees or between tall buildings.

And early in the morning or late at night, when temperatures drop near freezing.

If the road looks shiny but other cars aren''t kicking up spray, suspect ice. When you hit it, do nothing dramatic. Don''t brake. Don''t steer hard. Ease off the gas and let the car coast across.

Now, what if you start to skid. There are two main kinds.

The first is a rear-wheel skid — sometimes called a fishtail. The back of the car slides out. Look where you want to go. Steer gently in that direction. Don''t overcorrect, or the car will whip the other way.

The second is a front-wheel skid — called understeer. The car keeps going straight when you turn the wheel. Ease off the gas. Don''t add more steering. As the tires slow down, they''ll regrip and you can steer again.

In both cases, sudden braking makes things worse. Modern cars with anti-lock brakes will let you press the pedal firmly without locking up. But smooth pressure still beats panic.

Here''s something to take seriously. Stopping takes much longer. On packed snow, stopping distance can double. On ice, it can be 10 times longer than on dry pavement. That''s why looking far ahead matters so much. The earlier you see a red light, a stopped car, or a turn — the earlier you can start slowing down.

Approach intersections expecting that you might slide. Brake well before the line. If you''re not sure you can stop, start braking sooner — not harder.

Now, hills, bridges, and ramps. Going uphill, build a little momentum before the climb. Don''t try to power up a slick hill. Your wheels will just spin.

Going downhill, slow down before you start descending. Use a lower gear if your car has one, so the engine helps slow you.

And treat every bridge and overpass as if it''s iced over — even when other roads look fine.

Finally, the most important winter skill. Knowing when to just not go. If a storm warning is active, roads are unplowed, or you don''t have to be somewhere — wait. No errand is worth a crash. If you''re already out and conditions get bad, find a safe place to park and wait it out.' WHERE id = 'lesson_weather-driving_snow-and-ice';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Fog turns familiar roads into mystery roads. You can''t see far. You can''t judge speed well. And other cars appear out of nowhere. Heavy fog causes some of the worst chain-reaction crashes on highways — often with dozens of vehicles involved. The way you survive fog is to slow down, light up smartly, and resist the urge to follow other cars too closely.

Let''s start with why fog is so dangerous. Fog is just a cloud at ground level. It scatters light, hides distance, and tricks your brain. Three specific problems.

You can''t see far enough to react. At highway speeds, you may need 300 feet or more to stop. In thick fog, you might see only 100 feet.

Speed feels slower than it is. Without clear reference points whipping past, 50 miles per hour can feel like 30. People drive faster than they think.

And other drivers may panic. Some slam on brakes. Some stop in the road. Some don''t have lights on at all.

Now, using the right lights. This is where many drivers get it wrong. In fog — turn on your low beams, not high beams. High beams reflect off the fog and make a bright wall right in front of you.

If your car has fog lights, use them. They aim low and wide, under the fog layer.

Daytime running lights are not enough. They often don''t turn on your taillights — which is what cars behind you need to see.

And never drive with only parking lights. Use full headlights, even in daytime fog.

Next, slow down dramatically. Match your speed to what you can see. Here''s the simple rule. You should be able to stop within the distance your headlights show you. If visibility is half a block, you should be driving slow enough to stop in half a block.

Don''t trust the posted speed limit in fog. The limit assumes clear conditions. Foggy conditions ask you to choose a slower speed yourself.

And don''t tailgate the lights ahead. It''s tempting to find another car''s taillights and follow them through the fog. Don''t. If they brake suddenly or stop, you''ll hit them. Worse — they might be lost, drifting between lanes, or following someone else who is.

Leave extra following distance, even though it makes you feel more alone. Aim for at least double your normal gap.

Here''s a useful trick. Use the road, not the center line. Looking at the white line on the right edge of the road is usually better than staring at the dashed center line. Two reasons.

The right-edge line keeps you out of oncoming traffic.

And looking left toward oncoming headlights can dazzle you. That makes it harder to see anything else.

Keep your eyes moving. Avoid fixating on any single light source.

Now, fog isn''t the only thing that drops your sight distance. You''ll face the same challenge in heavy rain or snow squalls that hide the road ahead.

In smoke from wildfires or controlled burns.

In dust storms in dry, windy areas.

And in sun glare at sunrise and sunset. Especially when driving east in the morning, or west in the evening.

For sun glare, use your visor. Wear polarized sunglasses. And keep your windshield clean inside and out. A dirty windshield turns sun glare into total whiteout.

Sometimes the right answer is to stop. But how you stop matters.

Do not stop in the travel lane. Cars behind you can''t see you in time.

Do not stop on the shoulder if you can avoid it. Other drivers sometimes drift toward taillights they see in the fog — and hit parked cars.

The safest option is to pull completely off the road. Into a parking lot, gas station, or rest area. Turn off your lights, including taillights, so other drivers don''t follow them off the road. Then wait until visibility improves.' WHERE id = 'lesson_weather-driving_fog-and-low-visibility';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Wind doesn''t get the same respect as snow or rain. But it can shove your car across a lane, flip trailers, and turn debris into projectiles. Extreme weather — like thunderstorms, hail, heat waves, and severe wind events — also brings problems most new drivers haven''t thought about. This lesson covers how to handle conditions that show up suddenly, and how to spot when it''s time to get off the road.

Let''s start with driving in strong wind. Wind affects your car in three main ways.

Steady crosswinds push the car sideways, especially on bridges and open highways.

Gusts hit suddenly and can jerk the wheel out of a loose grip.

And wind from passing trucks creates a sudden push, then a pull as the truck passes you.

Here''s how to handle it. Keep both hands firmly on the wheel.

Slow down. Lower speeds give you more time to correct.

Anticipate where wind will hit hardest. Bridges, overpasses, gaps between buildings, tunnel exits, and open stretches with no trees.

And give large vehicles extra room. High-profile trucks, recreational vehicles, and trailers can be blown into your lane.

If you drive a sport utility vehicle, pickup, or anything tall — you''re more affected by wind than a low sedan. That doesn''t mean don''t drive. It just means stay alert and slow down sooner.

Now, watch for blown debris. Strong wind throws things into the road. Branches, trash cans, tarps, even sheet metal off truck loads. Scan farther ahead than usual. If something is in your lane, brake straight ahead rather than swerving when possible. A controlled hit at low speed is often safer than a loss of control at high speed.

Be especially careful behind trucks carrying loose cargo. Drop back. If something flies off — you want time and space.

Next, thunderstorms. Thunderstorms combine several hazards. Heavy rain, wind gusts, lightning, and sometimes hail. The biggest mistakes drivers make.

Driving into water across the road, because the storm makes it hard to judge depth.

Stopping under highway overpasses to shelter. This blocks lanes and creates pileups. It also doesn''t protect you from lightning or tornadoes.

And continuing to drive when visibility drops to almost nothing.

If a storm gets severe, exit the highway and find real shelter. A gas station, a store, anywhere with a solid roof. Stay in your car if you can''t reach a building. But never under an overpass.

Lightning is rarely a direct threat inside a car. The metal shell carries the charge around you. Just don''t touch metal parts of the interior during a strike. And avoid stopping under tall isolated trees.

Now, hail. Hail can crack windshields and dent body panels. If you get caught in a hailstorm, slow down. Don''t slam the brakes.

If safe, pull under cover. Like a gas station canopy, an overpass exit ramp shoulder well away from traffic, or a parking garage.

Face away from the hail if you can. The windshield is stronger than side windows.

And stay in the car. The roof protects you.

Next, extreme heat. Heat doesn''t make the road slippery. But it stresses your car and your judgment.

Tires can blow out more easily when pavement is very hot — especially if they''re underinflated.

Engines can overheat, especially in slow traffic.

Cabin temperatures climb fast. Never leave a child or pet in a parked car, even with windows cracked. It can become deadly in minutes.

And stay hydrated. Drowsiness from heat affects your reaction time.

If your engine starts to overheat, turn off the air conditioning. Turn the heater on full — it pulls heat from the engine. Then pull over as soon as it''s safe.

Now, severe weather warnings. If you hear a tornado warning or severe thunderstorm warning while driving — get off the road and into a solid building if you can.

Do not try to outrun a tornado in a car. Tornadoes change direction and move fast.

And if no shelter exists and the tornado is approaching, leave the car. Lie flat in a ditch or low spot. Cover your head. A car is one of the worst places to be in a tornado.

Here''s the overall theme of severe weather. Your trip is never as important as your safety. Pulling over, turning around, or waiting an hour costs nothing compared to a crash.' WHERE id = 'lesson_weather-driving_wind-and-extreme-weather';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Driving is a constant stream of small decisions. How hard to brake. When to look left. Whether that cyclist is about to swerve. You make hundreds of these every mile without noticing. Impairment is anything that slows those decisions down — makes them wrong — or convinces you they''re fine when they aren''t.

Let''s start with the three things impairment attacks. Almost every impairment problem comes down to damage in one or more of these.

First, reaction time. That''s how long between seeing a problem and your foot moving. Sober, alert drivers take about three quarters of a second. Tired or impaired — that can double or triple. At 45 miles per hour, an extra second is another 66 feet of car traveling toward whatever scared you.

Second, judgment. That''s picking the right move. An impaired brain underestimates risk, overestimates skill, and stops planning more than one step ahead.

Third, attention. That''s holding several things in your head at once. The car ahead. The light changing. The kid on the curb. The speedometer. Impairment narrows your focus to one thing at a time — often the wrong thing.

A driver who is a little slower, a little worse at judging gaps, and a little less able to track everything at once — is not a slightly worse driver. They''re a significantly more dangerous one. Because driving safely depends on all three working together.

Now here''s the cruel part. Why impaired drivers don''t feel impaired. The same systems that drive a car well are the ones that notice when something is wrong with you. When those systems are degraded, the warning light goes out at the same time the engine starts failing. This is why people who are clearly impaired say they feel fine to drive. They aren''t lying. Their brain genuinely can''t tell.

Two consequences from that.

You can''t trust your own I''m-good feeling, once anything has changed your brain chemistry or sleep state.

And you have to decide ahead of time — while sober and rested — what counts as not driving. The decision has to be made before the moment of getting behind the wheel.

Let''s talk about what impairment actually looks like behind the wheel. It''s rarely the dramatic swerving you see in movies. It''s quieter. And more common.

Drifting a few inches inside the lane, then overcorrecting.

Braking later than you meant to. Again and again.

Missing a turn you''ve made a hundred times.

Following too close, because you didn''t notice the gap shrinking.

Running a yellow that you would have stopped for any other day.

Any one of these can be the moment somebody on a bike or in a crosswalk gets hit.

The rest of this module breaks impairment into four pieces. They all hit the same three targets — reaction, judgment, attention.

Fatigue. Sleep loss and drowsy driving. Legal, common, and badly underestimated.

Alcohol. What it does to your brain and body — and why a little still matters for a new driver.

Other drugs. Cannabis, prescriptions, over-the-counter meds, and combinations. None of them make you a better driver.

And distraction. Phones, passengers, food, the radio, your own thoughts. Distraction is impairment you choose in the moment.

Here''s your job as a new driver. You are not yet a driver who can absorb a little extra risk. You don''t have the years of pattern recognition that let experienced drivers catch their own small mistakes. Anything that makes you slower, less attentive, or less honest with yourself stacks on top of being new. That is the gap that gets new drivers killed — and gets other people killed by new drivers.

The goal of this module is not to scare you. It''s to give you a clear picture of what each kind of impairment does to you.

A pre-decided plan for what you do instead of driving, when you''re not fit to.

And words you can use, in the moment, to refuse a ride or tell a passenger to stop.

The choice to not drive impaired is almost never made in the car. It''s made when you decide who''s driving home before you leave. When you set your phone down before you start the engine. And when you decide that being late or inconvenient is better than being the reason something terrible happened.' WHERE id = 'lesson_impairment-and-distraction_why-impairment-changes-the-driver-you-are';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Tired driving doesn''t feel like impaired driving. It feels normal. Then boring. Then suddenly — you can''t remember the last mile. That''s not a quirk. That''s your brain switching off in pieces, while the car keeps going.

Let''s start with what sleep loss actually does. Going without enough sleep doesn''t just make you yawn. It produces effects measurably similar to alcohol.

Slower reaction time.

Worse judgment, especially about your own state.

Narrowed attention. You stop scanning and start staring.

And microsleeps. Those are brief lapses where your brain goes offline for one to several seconds, while your eyes may stay open.

A microsleep of 4 seconds at highway speed means your car traveled the length of a basketball court — with no one in charge of it.

Here''s the hard truth. You can''t push through it. The popular fixes don''t really work.

Rolling down the windows wakes you for a minute. Then you adjust.

Loud music does the same thing.

Caffeine helps, but takes 20 to 30 minutes to kick in. It wears off unevenly. It can''t replace sleep, only delay the crash.

And just five more miles is the most dangerous thought a tired driver has. Because the brain making that decision is the one that''s failing.

The only real fix for sleepiness is sleep.

Now, when are you at highest risk. Drowsy crashes cluster in predictable windows.

Late night and early morning. Roughly midnight to 6 a.m. That''s when your body wants to be asleep, no matter how much you slept earlier.

Early afternoon, when there''s a natural dip in alertness.

After a long day of school, sports, or work — even if you don''t feel obviously tired.

On long, monotonous drives. Especially highways with little to look at.

And after missing even one night of normal sleep. You don''t have to be up for 24 hours to be dangerous.

New drivers are especially exposed. Because your schedule probably includes early school mornings, late practices or jobs, and weekends with late nights and early commitments. The math of teenage life adds up to chronic short sleep.

Let''s talk about warning signs you should not ignore. If any of these happen while you''re driving — you are already too tired to be driving safely.

Heavy or burning eyelids.

Frequent yawning that you can''t control.

Drifting within your lane, or hitting a rumble strip.

Missing an exit or turn you knew was coming.

Realizing you don''t remember the last few minutes of driving.

Or repeatedly losing track of your speed.

These are not signs to push harder. They are signs to get off the road.

Here''s what to do instead. A real plan for fatigue is built before you''re tired.

Treat sleep as part of the trip. If you know you have a long drive tomorrow, your bedtime tonight is part of the drive.

Don''t start a long drive after a full day. Driving home after a 12-hour day is one of the highest-risk things you can do.

Take a real break, not a fake one. A 20-minute nap in a safe parking spot beats two more coffees.

Bring someone. A passenger who is also awake can help you stay alert and call out drift. A passenger who is asleep does not count.

Pull over the moment you feel any warning sign. Find a safe, lit place. Lock the doors. Set an alarm. Nap.

And call for a ride. A late ride from a parent or friend is always cheaper than a crash. Decide in advance that this is allowed.

Now, saying no to a tired drive. A lot of teen driving fatigue comes from social pressure. Late events. Sleepovers. Working a closing shift. Then someone asks you to drive. You''re allowed to say no. Some lines that work.

I''m too tired to be safe right now. Can someone else drive, or can we wait?

I''m going to nap for 20 minutes before I head out.

Or — I can pick you up, but not until I''ve slept.

If you''re the passenger and the driver looks wrecked, you''re allowed to say no too. You look exhausted. I''d rather get a ride or wait. That''s a complete sentence. Sleeping in the passenger seat while someone else fights to stay awake is not a plan. It''s a gamble.

The rule is simple. If your body is trying to sleep — do not be the one driving the car.' WHERE id = 'lesson_impairment-and-distraction_drowsy-driving-and-fatigue';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Alcohol and other drugs change the chemistry of your brain. Driving is a brain task. There is no version of a little that leaves your driving untouched. This lesson is about what these substances actually do to you behind the wheel — and how to build a plan, so you never have to make the impaired-or-not decision in a parking lot at midnight.

Let''s start with what alcohol does to a driver. Alcohol is a depressant. It slows down the parts of your brain that handle several key things.

Reaction time. Even small amounts measurably slow how fast you respond to a brake light.

Coordination. Steering smoothly, braking the right amount, keeping a steady lane.

Tracking objects. Your eyes have a harder time following a moving target. Like a kid on a bike, or a car merging.

Judgment. This is the cruel part. Alcohol impairs the brain''s ability to notice it''s impaired. The drunker you are, the more confident you feel.

And multitasking. Driving is constant multitasking. Alcohol makes it harder to do two things at once — exactly when you most need to.

For a brand-new driver, even amounts that wouldn''t legally count as drunk for an adult are enough to wreck the margin you''d otherwise have to catch a mistake.

Now, why buzzed still counts. People tend to picture impaired driving as someone obviously drunk. The reality is that crashes happen at low levels too.

A driver who is just buzzed still has slower reactions and worse judgment than a sober driver.

They''re also more likely to take a risk they''d normally skip. A yellow light. A faster lane change. A shorter following distance.

And they''re far more likely to drive at all. Because the same alcohol that slowed their brain also convinced them they''re fine.

For a new driver, the safe number is zero. Not because of any specific rule — but because you don''t have the experience to absorb the loss.

Now let''s talk about cannabis. That includes marijuana, products containing THC, edibles, and vapes. Cannabis is not a safe alternative to alcohol behind the wheel. Research consistently shows it slows reaction time.

It impairs lane-keeping and following distance.

It distorts your sense of time and speed.

And it reduces your ability to divide attention between tasks.

A few specific traps. Edibles can hit much later than expected. You might feel fine when you start driving — and severely impaired 45 minutes in.

I drive better high is a classic example of impaired judgment. Not evidence. Studies consistently show the opposite.

And mixing cannabis and alcohol is worse than either alone. The effects multiply.

Next, prescription and over-the-counter meds. Legal does not mean safe to drive on. Some common offenders.

Allergy medications, especially older antihistamines, can cause significant drowsiness.

Cold and flu medicines often contain ingredients that impair alertness or coordination.

Pain medications, especially opioids, are seriously impairing.

Anti-anxiety, sleep, and muscle-relaxant medications are not compatible with driving.

And ADHD or other stimulant medications — when taken outside of how they were prescribed — can also impair driving.

Here are some rules of thumb. Read the label. If it says don''t operate heavy machinery, that includes a car.

Don''t drive on a new medication until you know how it affects you.

And combinations matter. Two mild things together can equal one strong impairment.

Now, building a no-impaired-driving plan. The goal is to never have to decide while you''re impaired. You decide while sober.

Pick a ride before you go out. Designated sober driver, parent pickup, rideshare, public transit, staying over. The plan exists before the event.

Pre-load the ride money. If a rideshare home costs money, have it ready. Decide it''s already spent.

Have a no-questions-asked agreement with a parent, older sibling, or trusted adult. I can call for a ride from anywhere, anytime, and we deal with the rest later. This single agreement has saved enormous numbers of lives.

Keep your keys out of reach if you might be tempted. Hand them to someone sober when you arrive.

And plan for the friend who might drive impaired. Decide in advance — you will take their keys, call them a ride, or call someone who can come get both of you.

Finally, being the passenger. You''re also responsible for not getting in the car with an impaired driver. Some lines that work.

I''m going to grab a ride. You should too.

I''ll wait with you until your ride comes.

Or — I''m not getting in. Let''s call someone.

It''s awkward for a minute. It''s awkward for a long time, if something happens.

Here''s the summary. Alcohol and drugs change the brain you drive with. Build the plan before you need it — so you never have to trust your impaired brain to make the right call.' WHERE id = 'lesson_impairment-and-distraction_alcohol-and-other-drugs';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Distraction is impairment you choose in the moment. Unlike fatigue or alcohol — you can usually fix it instantly. That''s the good news. The bad news is that distraction is constant. Socially normal. And built into the device in your pocket.

Let''s start with the three kinds of distraction. Every distraction is at least one of these.

Visual. Your eyes leave the road. Looking at a phone, the radio, a passenger, a billboard.

Manual. Your hands leave the wheel. Typing, eating, reaching into a bag, adjusting controls.

And cognitive. Your mind leaves the drive. Thinking through a conversation, an argument, a song lyric, what you''re going to say next.

The worst distractions hit all three at once. Texting is the classic example. Eyes on the screen. Hands off the wheel. Brain on the message.

Now, what a couple of seconds really means. Look away from the road for 2 seconds at 55 miles per hour, and your car has traveled more than half the length of a football field. 5 seconds — the average time it takes to read a text — is about 360 feet at that speed. That''s longer than many city blocks. All driven completely blind.

The road doesn''t pause while you look down. A child can step out. A car can stop. A light can change. A tire can blow. You don''t get those seconds back.

Let''s talk about phones. They''re the biggest distraction, on purpose. Phones are designed to be hard to ignore. Notifications, streaks, group chats, snap maps — all of it is engineered to pull your attention away from whatever you''re doing. While driving, that engineering is working against you.

A few honest things. Hands-free is better than handheld. But not safe. The cognitive distraction stays.

I only look at red lights still teaches your brain to check the phone in the car. The habit leaks into moving traffic.

And I can drive and text is a confidence not backed by reaction-time data. Drivers consistently overestimate their ability here.

Here are practical phone rules that actually work. The goal is to make the phone a non-decision while you drive.

Turn on Do Not Disturb While Driving — or your phone''s equivalent. It auto-silences notifications and can auto-reply.

Put the phone out of reach. Glove box, bag in the back seat, anywhere you can''t grab it without stopping.

Set navigation and music before you put the car in drive. Lock in your destination and playlist at the curb.

If you need to use the phone, pull over. A parking lot, a side street, a driveway. Stopped means stopped — in park.

And tell people the rule. If I don''t text back for a while, I''m driving. Set the expectation once. Stop apologizing for it.

Now, passengers. Passengers are the other big distraction for new drivers, especially other teens. More teen passengers in a car driven by a teen means a measurably higher crash risk. The combination of social pressure, conversation, and showing off is a real factor.

Here''s what helps. Keep early solo and friend drives short and familiar. You''re still building basic skills. Don''t add a carful of friends to your first month.

Set the ground rules out loud. I need to focus, so I''m going to be quieter in traffic. Most friends will respect it.

Pull over for anything serious. If a conversation needs your full attention, the conversation can wait until you''re parked.

And don''t perform. Driving fast, taking corners hard, or showing off for passengers is a leading cause of teen crashes. The audience is not worth it.

The smaller distractions add up too. Not all distractions look like a phone.

Eating and drinking take a hand and some attention. Save it for stops.

Adjusting climate, audio, or navigation mid-drive. Do it before you move, or at a long red.

Pets loose in the car. Pets belong restrained — not in your lap.

Reaching for dropped items. A dropped phone or fries are not worth a crash. Leave it. Get it when you stop.

And strong emotions. Driving right after a fight, a breakup, or terrible news is genuinely dangerous. Your cognitive attention is gone. Sit for a few minutes before you turn the key.

Here''s a simple pre-drive ritual. Build a 10-second routine before every drive.

First — seat, mirrors, seatbelt.

Second — phone on Do Not Disturb and out of reach.

Third — navigation and music set.

Fourth — passengers briefed if needed.

Fifth — quick check-in with yourself. Am I awake, calm, and ready?

If the answer to step five is no — you have permission to wait a few minutes, walk it off, or get a ride.

Here''s the core idea. You cannot drive well while doing something else. The car is not a place to multitask. Every time you give the road your full attention, you are doing the actual job of driving. Every time you don''t — you are gambling with somebody''s life. Often a stranger''s. Decide now what you''ll do with your phone, your passengers, and your attention — so you don''t have to decide it at 45 miles per hour.' WHERE id = 'lesson_impairment-and-distraction_distraction-and-staying-focused';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Pedestrians are the most vulnerable people on the road. They have no airbags. No seatbelts. No metal frame around them. When a car and a person collide — the person loses. That makes the driver responsible for paying extra attention. Even when a pedestrian does something unexpected.

Let''s start with where to expect pedestrians. They can appear almost anywhere, but some places demand extra caution.

Marked crosswalks at intersections.

Unmarked crosswalks. Every intersection legally has one, even without paint.

School zones, parks, and playgrounds.

Parking lots, especially near store entrances.

Bus stops and transit centers.

Residential streets, where kids might run between parked cars.

And downtown areas with heavy foot traffic.

At night, in rain, or in fog — pedestrians get much harder to see. Dark clothing, hoods, and umbrellas hide people. Slow down when visibility drops.

Now, yielding the right of way. The general rule across the country is simple. Yield to pedestrians in crosswalks. That means slow down or stop and let them cross before you go. Even when a pedestrian is technically jaywalking, you still have to try to avoid hitting them. Being legally right does not undo a tragedy.

When you approach a crosswalk — cover the brake with your foot.

Scan both sidewalks, not just the road ahead.

Make eye contact with anyone near the curb.

And wait until the pedestrian is fully across your lane, plus a safety margin.

Here''s a big one. The hidden-pedestrian problem. If the car next to you stops at a crosswalk for no obvious reason — do not pass it. That driver almost certainly stopped for a pedestrian you cannot see. Drivers in the second lane cause many of the worst crosswalk crashes, because they sweep around the stopped car at full speed.

The rule is — when a vehicle is stopped at a crosswalk, stop too. Then look.

Now, backing up. More kids are hit in driveways and parking lots than people realize. Before backing up — walk around the vehicle, if you have been parked for a while.

Check the rear camera. And look over your shoulder.

Back slowly, so you have time to react.

And stop completely if you hear a horn, a shout, or a thump.

Rear cameras have blind spots. They do not see a toddler crouched right behind a bumper.

Let''s talk about school zones and buses. School zones often have lower speed limits when children are present. Sometimes as low as 15 to 20 miles per hour. Obey the posted limit. Stay off your phone. Kids are unpredictable. A ball rolling into the street usually means a child is about to follow.

Now, pedestrians with disabilities. A person using a white cane or a guide dog has the right of way at all times. Do not honk to hurry them. They may be listening for traffic to judge when to cross. Idle quietly and let them finish.

Here''s something important. Driving while distracted is even worse around pedestrians. Looking at your phone for 2 seconds at 30 miles per hour means you travel almost 90 feet blind. That''s more than enough distance to miss a child stepping off a curb. In any pedestrian-heavy area — your phone goes down, and your eyes go up.

Finally, a simple habit. Every time you approach an intersection, do a quick sidewalk-to-sidewalk sweep before you commit to the turn or the crossing. That one-second habit prevents the kind of crash you never recover from emotionally.' WHERE id = 'lesson_sharing-the-road_pedestrians-and-crosswalks';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Bicycles and motorcycles share the road with cars — but have almost none of the protection. A rider has no crumple zone. No airbags. No roof. A small mistake from a driver can put a rider in the hospital. Treating them with respect is not optional. It is part of the job.

Let''s start with cyclists. They belong on the road. In most places, bicycles are legally considered vehicles. They have the right to use the travel lane. Not just the shoulder or a bike lane. A cyclist may move toward the center of the lane to avoid potholes, parked-car doors, debris — or to make a left turn. That''s not them being rude. That''s them protecting their life.

Now, passing a cyclist. Give cyclists wide space when passing.

Aim for at least 3 feet of clearance. More at higher speeds.

Slow down before you pass. Do not speed up to get around.

Wait for a safe gap, even if it costs you a few seconds.

And never squeeze past a cyclist when an oncoming car is close.

A gust of wind from a passing truck can knock a cyclist off balance. Your car, passing inches away — feels like the same thing.

Here''s something most drivers forget. The dooring danger. If you are parked on the street, look before opening your door. A cyclist coming up alongside has almost no time to swerve. The safe move is the reach-across habit. Open the driver door with your right hand. That forces your body to turn and look back. And you naturally see anyone approaching.

Next, watch at intersections. Most car-versus-bike crashes happen at intersections — not on open roads. Here are the common ones.

The right hook. A driver turns right across a cyclist going straight.

The left cross. A driver turning left fails to see an oncoming cyclist.

And the pull-out. A driver leaving a driveway looks for cars, but not for bikes.

The fix is simple. Actively look for narrow shapes, not just car-sized ones. Bicycles are easy to miss, because your brain filters for vehicles your size.

Now let''s talk about motorcycles. A motorcycle is entitled to the full width of a lane. Never try to share a lane with one, or squeeze past in the same lane. Their position inside the lane is intentional. They shift left, center, or right to stay visible — and to avoid oil, sand, and uneven pavement.

Motorcycles hide in your blind spots. Because they''re narrow, they can vanish behind your A-pillars, in your mirrors, or behind another car. Before any lane change — signal early.

Check the mirror.

Turn your head and check the blind spot directly.

And do it again if traffic is heavy.

A motorcycle that was clearly visible 3 seconds ago might now be right next to your door.

Following distance changes too. Motorcycles can stop much faster than cars in many situations, especially on dry pavement. Tailgating one means you may not be able to stop in time if they brake hard. Give at least a 4-second following gap behind a motorcycle. More in rain, or on loose surfaces.

Now, weather makes everything worse. Rain, wet leaves, painted lines, metal grates, and gravel are all dangerous for two-wheeled vehicles. A rider may slow down, change lane position, or brake earlier than you expect. Give them more room in bad weather — not less.

Finally, the mindset shift. The single best habit you can build is this. Assume there is always a cyclist or motorcyclist nearby that you have not noticed yet. That assumption makes you check twice, signal earlier, and leave more space. None of that costs you real time. All of it could save someone''s life.' WHERE id = 'lesson_sharing-the-road_cyclists-and-motorcyclists';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Big rigs, dump trucks, delivery trucks, and buses are not just bigger cars. They accelerate slower. They stop slower. They turn wider. And they have huge blind spots. Driving around them safely means understanding how they actually work — not just staying out of their way.

Now, about those blind spots. They are massive. Large trucks have four major blind spots, often called the No Zones.

The first is directly in front, about 20 feet ahead of the cab.

The second is directly behind, about 30 feet behind the trailer.

The third runs along the driver''s side, under the side mirror.

The fourth runs along the passenger side, extending across two lanes.

Here''s a useful rule. If you cannot see the truck driver''s face in their side mirror — they cannot see you. Lingering in a blind spot is one of the most dangerous things you can do on the highway.

Let''s talk about passing a truck. Pass on the left whenever possible, since the right-side blind spot is bigger.

Maintain a steady speed. Do not creep along beside the trailer.

Get clearly ahead before merging back. You should see the entire cab in your rearview mirror.

And never cut in front and brake. The truck cannot stop the way you can.

A loaded semi traveling 65 miles per hour may need the length of two football fields to stop. If you brake-check a truck — the truck wins.

Now, about wide turns. Trucks and buses need to swing wide to make turns, especially right turns. The trailer tracks inside the path of the cab. If a truck has its right turn signal on and is drifting left — do not try to squeeze up the right side. You will be crushed against the curb.

Watch for these clues. A right turn signal blinking. The cab swinging left into your lane. Slow speed approaching an intersection.

When in doubt, hang back and let the truck complete the turn.

Following distance matters too. Following a large truck too closely creates two problems. First, you cannot see around it, so you have no idea what traffic ahead is doing. Second, if anything falls off the truck — you have no time to react. Drop back so you can see at least one full vehicle length of road between your hood and the rear of the trailer at highway speeds. Ideally more.

If a truck is behind you and following too closely, do not brake to send a message. Change lanes when you can and let them pass. A panicked truck driver behind you is the last thing you want.

Wind and spray are another factor. Passing a large truck on the highway in rain can soak your windshield in a single second. Turn on your wipers before you start the pass — not after. Crosswinds also push small cars around when they exit the truck''s wind shadow. Keep both hands on the wheel.

Now, school buses. They get extra legal protection because they carry kids who often dart across the road. When a school bus extends its stop arm and flashes red lights, traffic in both directions usually must stop. The few exceptions involve divided highways with a physical barrier. When in doubt — stop. The cost of being wrong is a child''s life.

Even after the lights turn off, scan for kids still crossing or running toward the bus. Pull away slowly.

Transit and city buses are a different story. They pull in and out of traffic constantly. Many places require drivers to yield to a bus that is signaling to pull out from a stop. Even where it is not required, giving them space keeps traffic moving smoothly. And watch for pedestrians stepping out from in front of a stopped bus.

Here''s the big mindset. A truck driver doing their job well is not your enemy. They want to get home too. Most truck crashes that involve a car are caused by the car driver — not the trucker. Give them space. Stay visible. And never assume they can react as quickly as you can. Physics is not on their side.' WHERE id = 'lesson_sharing-the-road_large-trucks-and-buses';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Some of the most stressful moments behind the wheel involve flashing lights. A fire truck behind you. A tow truck on the shoulder. A flagger waving a sign in a construction zone. These situations have clear rules — and following them protects people who are doing some of the most dangerous jobs on the road.

Let''s start with what to do when you hear a siren. The first thing to do is figure out where it is coming from. Sirens echo between buildings and can sound like they are everywhere at once.

Turn down the radio.

Check all your mirrors.

Look left, right, and ahead at intersections.

Roll down a window briefly if you need to locate the sound.

Do not assume the siren is for someone else. Find it before you decide what to do.

Now, pulling over. The general rule across the country — when an emergency vehicle approaches with lights and siren, pull as far to the right as you can and stop. Then stay there until it passes.

A few important details. Use your turn signal so other drivers know your plan.

Do not slam on the brakes in the middle of a lane.

Do not stop in an intersection. Clear the intersection first, then pull right.

On a one-way street with no right shoulder, pulling left may be allowed.

On a divided highway, vehicles on the opposite side may not need to stop — but stay alert.

If you are at a red light and an emergency vehicle is behind you, do not run the light. Stay put unless you can safely and legally move to clear a path. The emergency driver is trained to navigate around stopped traffic.

Here''s a temptation to resist. Never follow an emergency vehicle. It can feel smart to tuck in behind a fire truck or ambulance to slip through traffic. Do not do it. In most places it is illegal. And it puts you in the path of other emergency vehicles that may be following — or approaching from a different direction.

Next, move-over laws. When you see flashing lights on the shoulder — whether police, fire, ambulance, tow truck, or road maintenance — you have two responsibilities.

Move over one lane away from them if it is safe to do so.

If you cannot move over, slow down significantly below the posted limit.

These laws exist because roadside workers are struck and killed every year by drivers who did not give them room. A few seconds of inconvenience is nothing compared to a tow operator''s life.

Now let''s talk about work zones. Work zones change the road temporarily, and they are full of hazards. Workers on foot. Narrowed lanes. Sudden stops. Uneven pavement. Equipment crossing your path. Speed limits in work zones are usually lower and often carry doubled fines.

Driving safely through a work zone means a few specific things.

Slow down as soon as you see the orange signs — not when you reach the cones.

Increase your following distance. Traffic stops fast in work zones.

Watch for flaggers and obey their signals over any traffic light or sign.

Merge early when a lane closure is announced. Not at the last second.

And stay off the phone. Completely.

Flaggers have legal authority to direct traffic. A flagger holding a stop paddle means stop — even if the light ahead is green.

Now, funeral processions. If you encounter one, the lead car typically has its headlights and flashers on, and following cars do too. Do not cut into the line. Let it pass. Many places give the procession the right of way through intersections, even against a red light.

After the emergency passes, you still need to be careful. Once the emergency vehicle is well past you, signal, check your mirrors and blind spot, and merge back into the lane carefully. Other drivers may pull out at the same time — so do not just shoot back into traffic.

Here''s the bottom line. Flashing lights mean someone is having the worst day of their life — or working to prevent yours. Treat every emergency scene, work zone, and roadside breakdown as a place where the rules tighten and your attention sharpens. The people in those reflective vests are counting on you.' WHERE id = 'lesson_sharing-the-road_emergency-vehicles-and-work-zones';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'A skid happens when your tires lose their grip on the road. Once that grip is gone — steering and braking stop working the way you expect. Most skids come from doing too much, too fast. Too much brake. Too much gas. Or too much steering for the conditions. Rain, snow, ice, gravel, and even painted lines can take grip away in a heartbeat.

The single best thing you can do about skids is prevent them. Slow down before a curve — not in it. Increase your following distance when the road is wet or cold. Look far ahead so you spot shiny pavement, slush, or leaves before you reach them. Smooth inputs on the wheel, gas, and brake keep your tires loaded evenly and gripping.

Now, there are three common skids to know.

The first is a rear-wheel skid, also called oversteer. The back of the car slides out sideways. The car wants to spin.

The second is a front-wheel skid, also called understeer. You turn the wheel — but the car keeps going straight. This is common when you brake and turn at the same time on a slick road.

The third is a four-wheel skid. All four tires lock or slide. You feel like you are gliding with no control.

Let''s walk through how to recover from each one. Start with a rear-wheel skid.

First, ease off the gas. Do not stab the brake.

Second, look where you want the car to go — not at what you are sliding toward.

Third, steer gently in the same direction the rear is sliding. If the back swings right, steer right.

Fourth, as the car straightens, smoothly straighten the wheel. Do not over-correct, or the car will fishtail the other way.

Now, a front-wheel skid. First, ease off the gas or brake — whichever you were doing.

Second, hold the wheel pointed where you want to go. But do not crank it harder. More steering input will not help when the front tires have no grip.

Third, wait a beat for the tires to regain traction.

Fourth, once you feel grip return, gently steer through the turn.

And finally, a four-wheel skid. First, take your feet off both pedals.

Second, keep the wheel pointed straight, or aimed where you want to go.

Third, let the car slow down on its own until the tires bite again.

Fourth, then steer and brake gently.

A quick word on anti-lock brakes. If your car has anti-lock brakes — almost all modern cars do — press the brake firmly and hold it down in an emergency. You will feel a buzzing or pulsing through the pedal. That is normal. Do not pump the pedal. Anti-lock brakes let you steer while you brake hard. That is the whole point.

Finally, hydroplaning. Hydroplaning is a skid on water. A thin layer of water lifts the tires off the pavement, usually above 35 miles per hour in heavy rain or through standing water. If it happens — do not brake hard.

Ease off the gas.

Keep the wheel straight and steady.

Wait for the tires to settle back onto the road, then continue.

Good tires with deep tread and correct air pressure are your best defense.' WHERE id = 'lesson_emergencies-and-breakdowns_skids-and-loss-of-traction';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'A blowout or a brake failure feels terrifying because the car suddenly does not respond the way it should. The good news — both have clear, learnable responses. The wrong instinct in either case is to slam on the brakes. Train yourself now, so your hands and feet know what to do before your brain catches up.

Let''s start with a tire blowout. A blowout is a sudden loss of tire pressure, usually with a loud bang. The car will pull hard toward the side of the failed tire. A front blowout pulls the steering wheel. A rear blowout makes the back of the car wag or fishtail.

Here''s what to do. First, grip the wheel firmly with both hands.

Second, do not slam the brakes. Hard braking shifts weight forward and can spin the car.

Third, ease off the gas and let the car slow down on its own.

Fourth, steer gently to keep the car going straight in your lane.

Fifth, once you are under about 30 miles per hour, lightly apply the brakes.

Sixth, signal and coast to the right shoulder — as far off the road as you safely can.

Seventh, turn on hazard lights. Exit on the side away from traffic if it is safe to do so.

To avoid blowouts in the first place, check tire pressure monthly. Look for bulges or cracks. Replace tires with worn tread. And do not overload the car.

Now, brake failure. Total brake failure is rare in modern cars, but partial loss of braking does happen — a soft pedal, a pedal sinking to the floor, or brakes that grab on one side.

If the pedal feels soft or sinks, do this. First, pump the brake pedal quickly several times. This can build pressure in the system and may restore some braking.

Second, if pumping does not help, shift to a lower gear. That means D2, L, or downshift a manual. Lower gears use the engine to slow the car.

Third, apply the parking brake slowly and steadily. Do not yank it on all at once or you can lock the rear wheels and spin. Most parking brake handles or pedals can be eased on gradually. If your car has an electronic parking brake, hold the switch and the system will apply gradually.

Fourth, steer toward an escape path. An empty shoulder. An uphill exit. An empty parking lot. Avoid oncoming traffic.

Fifth — and this is a last resort — rub the tires against a curb, or scrape the side of the car along a guardrail, to bleed off speed. Property damage beats hitting a person or another car.

Sixth, once stopped, turn on hazards and do not drive again until the brakes are fixed.

There''s one more emergency to cover. A stuck accelerator. If the gas pedal sticks down, first — shift to neutral. The engine will rev loudly, but the wheels will disconnect from the engine. This is the most important step.

Second, steer to a safe spot and brake normally.

Third, once stopped, turn the engine off. Do not turn the key all the way off while moving — or you will lose power steering and may lock the steering column.

Here''s the common thread. In every one of these emergencies, the right move is to stay off the brake at first, keep both hands on the wheel, and guide the car to a safe stopping place. Panic braking turns a manageable problem into a crash. Practice saying the steps out loud now — so they are there when you need them.' WHERE id = 'lesson_emergencies-and-breakdowns_tire-blowouts-and-brake-failure';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Cars give you warnings before most major failures. The trick is knowing which signals mean deal with it soon — and which mean pull over right now. This lesson covers the dashboard warnings that matter most, what to do if the engine stalls while you are moving, and how to handle the rare but serious situation of a vehicle fire.

Let''s start with reading warning lights. Not every light is an emergency. Color is your first clue.

Green or blue means a system is on. Headlights, high beams, cruise. Informational only.

Yellow or amber means something needs attention soon. Drive carefully and get it checked. Examples include the check engine light, low fuel, low tire pressure, and the anti-lock brake warning.

Red means stop as soon as it is safe. Red lights mean the car can hurt itself, you, or both. Examples include oil pressure, engine temperature, brake system, charging system, and airbag.

There are two red lights most worth memorizing.

The first is oil pressure — the oil can icon. The engine is not getting oil. Driving even a few more miles can destroy the engine. Pull over and shut it off.

The second is engine temperature — the thermometer icon. The engine is overheating. Keep driving and you risk a cracked head or a fire. Pull over, shut the engine off, and let it cool for at least 30 minutes before opening the hood.

And never open a hot radiator cap. Pressurized steam can spray and cause serious burns.

Now let''s talk about engine stalls. If the engine quits at speed, it''s startling — because the power steering gets heavy and the brakes get firm after one or two pumps. The car still steers and stops. It just takes more effort.

First, both hands on the wheel. Steer toward the shoulder.

Second, signal and check mirrors. Other drivers will not know you are losing power.

Third, brake firmly but smoothly. Power assist may be reduced, so push harder than usual.

Fourth, once on the shoulder, shift to park. For a manual, shift to neutral with parking brake on.

Fifth, try restarting. If it will not start, turn on hazards.

Sixth, get out on the side away from traffic if it is safe. Stand well off the road.

Now, vehicle fires. Car fires usually start small — in the engine bay or under the dash — and grow fast. Warning signs include smoke from under the hood, a burning smell, or flames visible anywhere.

If you see or smell fire while driving, first — signal and pull off the road right away. Get as far from traffic as you can.

Second, shut off the engine. This stops fuel from pumping.

Third, get everyone out. Do not stop to grab belongings.

Fourth, move at least 100 feet away. That''s about the length of two school buses. Move further if the fire is large or near the fuel tank.

Fifth, call 911. Tell them it is a vehicle fire and give your location.

Sixth — do not open the hood. Opening it gives the fire more oxygen and can cause flames to jump out at you.

Seventh, warn approaching traffic if you safely can. But never go back to the car.

A small fire extinguisher in the trunk can help with a tiny fire spotted early. But your safety always comes first. If you are not absolutely sure you can put it out in seconds — get away and let the fire department handle it.

One more thing. Smoke and steam are not the same.

White steam from under the hood usually means coolant is leaking or boiling. Pull over and shut off.

Blue or black smoke from the exhaust means an engine problem — but not usually an immediate fire risk. Drive gently to a safe stopping point.

Smoke from inside the dash or under the hood is a fire warning. Treat it as a fire until proven otherwise.

When in doubt — get out.' WHERE id = 'lesson_emergencies-and-breakdowns_engine-fires-stalls-and-warning-lights';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Even careful drivers end up in fender benders or stranded on the shoulder. Knowing what to do in the first few minutes keeps you safe, keeps the situation from getting worse, and protects you legally and financially. This lesson is your checklist for after the worst has already happened.

Let''s walk through a collision. The moments right after a crash are chaotic. Adrenaline makes it hard to think. Run through these steps in order.

First — stop. Leaving the scene of a crash, even a minor one, is a crime almost everywhere. Stop your vehicle.

Second, check yourself, then your passengers. Are you hurt? Is anyone bleeding, struggling to breathe, or unable to move? If yes, call 911 immediately.

Third, make the scene safer. If the cars can be driven and are blocking traffic, move them to the shoulder. If they cannot move, turn on hazard lights. Set out reflective triangles or flares if you have them.

Fourth, call for help. Call 911 for any crash with injuries, large vehicle damage, or a blocked roadway. Even for minor crashes, calling the non-emergency police line creates an official report. Many insurance companies require one.

Fifth, exchange information with the other driver. That means name, phone, address, driver''s license number, license plate, insurance company and policy number, and the make and model of their car.

Sixth, document the scene. Take photos of all vehicles from multiple angles. The license plates. The road. Skid marks. Traffic signs or signals. And any visible injuries. Note the time, weather, and street names.

Seventh, get witness info if anyone saw it. Names and phone numbers.

Eighth — do not admit fault. Do not argue. Do not say I''m sorry or it was my fault, even if you think it was. Let the police and insurance companies sort out responsibility based on evidence.

Ninth, notify your insurance company as soon as you can. Most have a 24-hour claims line and an app.

Tenth, tell a parent or guardian right away if you are a teen driver. They need to know, and they can help you handle the next steps.

If someone is seriously hurt, the rules tighten. Do not move them unless the car is on fire or in immediate danger. Moving someone with a neck or spine injury can paralyze them.

Call 911 and follow the dispatcher''s instructions.

If they are unconscious but breathing, stay with them and keep them calm.

Turn off the engines of damaged cars to reduce fire risk.

Now let''s shift to roadside breakdowns. A breakdown is not a crash — but it can become dangerous if you handle it badly. Cars stopped on the shoulder get hit by passing traffic every day.

When you sense trouble — a warning light, a strange noise, a loss of power — first, turn on your hazard lights early. Other drivers need warning.

Second, get to the right shoulder, an exit, or a parking lot. The further off the road, the safer.

Third, steer straight and park as far right as you can. If there is a wide shoulder or grass, use it.

Fourth, turn the wheels away from the road in case the car gets bumped.

Fifth, leave hazard lights on.

Sixth, set out reflective triangles or flares behind the car if you have them. One about 10 feet behind. One about 100 feet behind.

Here''s the most important decision after a breakdown. Should you get out of the car?

On a quiet road with a wide shoulder, exit on the passenger side away from traffic and stand well off the road, behind a guardrail if there is one.

On a busy highway with narrow shoulders, it is often safer to stay in the car with your seatbelt on and call for help. A car hit at highway speed is more survivable than a person standing next to it.

Never stand between your car and oncoming traffic. And never try to push a car out of a travel lane by yourself.

Calling for help works best when you''re ready. Know your roadside assistance number before you need it — insurance, auto club, or the car maker''s app. Be ready to share your location. That means nearest exit, mile marker, or cross streets.

The problem. A flat, dead battery, overheating, won''t start.

And whether you are in a safe spot or in traffic.

Finally, a breakdown kit pays for itself. Keep these in your trunk. Jumper cables or a portable jump pack. A flashlight. Reflective triangles. A phone charger. A basic first aid kit. Water. A blanket. And gloves. In cold climates, add a snow brush, ice scraper, and warm hat. You may go years without using any of it — then be very glad you have it on one bad night.' WHERE id = 'lesson_emergencies-and-breakdowns_collisions-and-roadside-breakdowns';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Auto insurance is a contract. You pay a company a regular fee. And in return, they agree to pay for certain costs if something goes wrong with your car — or if you cause harm to someone else. It exists because car crashes can cost more money than almost any teenager, or adult, has sitting in a bank account. A single crash with injuries can run into tens or hundreds of thousands of dollars. Insurance spreads that risk across a huge pool of drivers, so no one person gets wiped out by one bad day.

Let''s start with the words you need to know.

Premium. That''s the amount you pay the insurance company, usually every month or every six months. It is the price of the policy.

Policy. That''s the written contract. It lists what is covered, what is not, and how much the company will pay.

Deductible. That''s the amount you pay out of your own pocket before the insurance company pays anything. If your deductible is 500 dollars and the repair is 2,000 dollars — you pay 500 and the insurer pays 1,500.

Claim. That''s a request you file with the insurance company asking them to pay for a covered loss.

Coverage limit. That''s the maximum the insurance company will pay for a certain type of loss. Anything above that is on you.

Now, the main kinds of coverage. Almost every policy is built from a few standard pieces. You will see these on any insurance card or quote.

Liability coverage pays for damage and injuries you cause to other people and their property. If you rear-end someone, liability pays for their bumper and their hospital bill. It does not pay for your car or your injuries. Driving without liability coverage is illegal in essentially every state.

Collision coverage pays to repair your car when it is damaged in a crash — no matter who was at fault.

Comprehensive coverage pays for damage to your car from things that are not crashes. Theft. Hail. A tree falling. A deer running into the road. Vandalism. Fire.

Uninsured and underinsured motorist coverage protects you when the other driver caused the crash but does not have enough insurance, or any, to pay for your injuries or repairs.

Medical payments, sometimes called personal injury protection, helps cover medical bills for you and your passengers, regardless of fault.

Here''s how the premium gets calculated. Insurance companies try to predict how likely you are to file a claim. The more likely they think a claim is — the higher your premium.

A few things push a teen driver''s premium up. Being new to driving. Less experience equals more risk in the data.

Tickets, especially for speeding or reckless driving.

At-fault crashes.

Driving a car that is expensive to repair or commonly stolen.

And living somewhere with lots of traffic or theft.

A few things can lower it. Good grades. Many insurers offer a student discount.

Completing an approved driver education course.

Staying ticket-free and crash-free over time.

Choosing a higher deductible. You pay more out of pocket — but the monthly premium drops.

And being added to a parent''s policy instead of having your own.

Now, here''s what insurance does not do. Insurance is not a free pass. A few things to keep straight.

It does not erase a ticket or a citation. You still face fines and points.

It does not cover intentional damage. If you crash on purpose or drive drunk — claims can be denied.

It does not cover business use of your personal car unless you add it. This matters if you ever deliver food or drive for an app.

And it does not pay more than your coverage limits. If you cause 200,000 dollars in damage and you only have 50,000 dollars in liability — the other 150,000 can come from your savings, wages, or assets.

That last point is the real reason insurance matters. It is not just paperwork to make the law happy. It is the wall between one bad afternoon — and years of debt.' WHERE id = 'lesson_insurance-and-responsibility_how-auto-insurance-works';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Even careful drivers get into crashes. The goal of this lesson is simple. If it happens to you, you should know exactly what to do in the first ten minutes — because those minutes affect your safety, your legal standing, and your insurance claim.

Step one. Stop. Always stop.

If you are involved in a crash, you must stop. This is true even if the damage looks tiny. Even if no one seems hurt. And even if you only hit a parked car or a mailbox. Leaving the scene of a crash you were part of is a serious crime in every state — often a much bigger deal than the crash itself.

If you hit an unattended parked car, leave a note with your name, phone number, and a brief description of what happened. And report it.

Step two. Check for injuries. Before anything else, check yourself. Then check your passengers. Then, if it is safe, check the other vehicle.

If anyone is hurt, call emergency services right away.

Do not move someone who is injured unless they are in immediate danger — like a car on fire. Moving an injured person can make spinal injuries worse.

And if you are not sure whether someone is hurt, call for help anyway. Adrenaline hides pain.

Step three. Make the scene safer. A crash often turns into a second crash when other drivers come around a curve and do not see it in time. If the cars can be driven and you are blocking traffic — move them to the shoulder or a nearby parking lot.

Turn on hazard lights.

If you have flares or a reflective triangle, set them out.

If a car cannot be moved, get yourself and your passengers out and away from the roadway. Behind a barrier if possible.

Step four. Call the police. For anything beyond the most minor fender bender, call the police and ask for an officer to come to the scene. A police report is one of the most useful documents you can have when filing an insurance claim. Even in a small crash, a report helps protect you against false claims later.

While you wait, do not argue with the other driver about who is at fault. Do not say it was my fault. Do not say don''t worry about it. And do not promise to pay for anything out of pocket. Fault is for the insurance companies — and, if needed, the police — to determine.

Step five. Exchange information. Get, and give, the following. Full name and phone number.

Driver''s license number.

License plate number.

Insurance company name and policy number.

Make, model, and color of the vehicle.

If there are witnesses, ask for their names and phone numbers too. They can disappear fast once traffic clears.

Step six. Document everything. Your phone is your best tool here. Take photos of all damage to every vehicle involved — close up and from a few feet back.

The position of the cars before you move them, if possible.

The street, intersection, traffic signs, skid marks, and any debris.

The other driver''s insurance card and license. With permission, or just photograph the info.

And any visible injuries.

Write down, or voice-memo, what happened while it is fresh. The time. The weather. The direction each car was going. And what you remember seeing right before impact.

Step seven. Report it to your insurance company. Call your insurance company — or your parent''s, if you are on their policy — as soon as you reasonably can. Ideally that same day. Most policies require prompt reporting. Tell them the facts. Do not guess. Do not exaggerate. And do not minimize. If you do not remember something, say so.

Now, what not to do.

Do not flee, even if you are scared or unlicensed.

Do not post about the crash on social media. Insurance companies and lawyers can and do look at posts.

Do not sign anything from the other driver or a stranger at the scene.

And do not accept a quick cash offer to forget the whole thing. Hidden damage and hidden injuries often show up later. Once you accept money — your options shrink.

A crash is scary. Having a plan in your head ahead of time is the single best way to keep a bad moment from getting worse.' WHERE id = 'lesson_insurance-and-responsibility_at-the-scene-of-a-crash';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'The sticker price of a car is just the beginning. The real cost of owning a vehicle shows up month after month — and it surprises a lot of new drivers. Understanding the full picture helps you make a smart choice about what car to drive, when to drive it, and whether to drive at all on a given day.

Think of car ownership as five ongoing buckets — plus the price of the car itself.

The first is the car. Either an upfront purchase, or a monthly loan or lease payment. Plus sales tax and registration fees.

The second is fuel. Gas or electricity. It varies wildly with how much you drive and how efficient the car is.

The third is insurance. That was covered in detail in the first lesson of this module.

The fourth is maintenance. Routine work that keeps the car running.

The fifth is repairs. Fixing things that break or wear out.

And the sixth is fees and taxes. Registration. Inspection. Parking. Tolls.

Miss any one of these and you will eventually find yourself stuck on the side of the road — or unable to legally drive your car.

Let''s talk about routine maintenance you cannot skip. Maintenance is what you do before something breaks. And it is almost always cheaper than waiting for a failure.

Oil changes. Typically every few thousand miles, based on the owner''s manual. Old oil ruins engines.

Tire pressure. Check at least once a month. Low pressure costs you fuel and chews up tires.

Tire rotation and replacement. Tires wear unevenly. Rotating extends life. Bald tires are a crash waiting to happen, especially in rain or snow.

Brakes. Brake pads wear down. Squealing or grinding sounds mean it is time for a shop visit.

Fluids. Coolant. Brake fluid. Transmission fluid. Windshield washer fluid. Each has a job.

Lights and wipers. A burned-out brake light can get you pulled over — and is dangerous. Streaky wipers reduce visibility.

Battery. Most last a few years. Slow starts are an early warning.

Now, repairs. The surprise bucket. Even a well-maintained car will eventually need repairs. A new battery, a set of tires, or a brake job can each cost several hundred dollars. A failed transmission or engine can cost more than the car is worth. Build a small repair fund if you can. A common rule of thumb — try to save the equivalent of one car payment per month in a separate account, so a surprise repair doesn''t become a crisis.

Here''s the hidden cost. Depreciation. Cars lose value over time. A new car loses a big chunk of its value the moment you drive it off the lot, and continues to lose value every year. Used cars lose value more slowly. Which is one reason they are often a smarter first car for a teen driver. Depreciation isn''t a bill in your mailbox — but if you ever sell the car, you will feel it.

When you stack the buckets, owning even a modest used car often costs several hundred dollars a month — once you average out insurance, fuel, maintenance, and the occasional repair. That is real money. Before you commit to a car, sketch out a monthly budget that includes every bucket above. If the total doesn''t fit your income or your family''s plan — the car doesn''t fit either.

Let''s cover smart habits that save real money. Drive smoothly. Hard acceleration and hard braking waste fuel and wear out parts.

Combine trips. Cold engines use more fuel. One longer trip is more efficient than several short ones.

Keep tires properly inflated. It improves fuel economy and tire life.

Follow the maintenance schedule in the owner''s manual. It is written for your specific car.

Compare gas prices — but don''t drive ten miles out of your way to save two cents a gallon.

Address small issues early. A small leak ignored becomes a big repair.

And don''t ignore warning lights. A check-engine light is the car telling you something. Get it scanned.

One more thought. Driving less is also a choice. The cheapest mile is the one you don''t drive. Carpooling, biking, walking, and public transit all reduce wear on your car — and your wallet. Being a responsible driver also means recognizing when driving isn''t the right call.' WHERE id = 'lesson_insurance-and-responsibility_the-real-cost-of-owning-a-car';
UPDATE lesson SET narrationScript = 'Being a responsible driver sounds vague until you break it down into habits. Responsibility is not a personality trait. It is a set of small choices you make every time you get behind the wheel. Done consistently, those choices keep you, your passengers, and everyone else on the road safer.

Let''s start before you drive. Responsibility starts before the engine is on.

Are you fit to drive? Driving impaired by alcohol, drugs — including some prescriptions — or extreme tiredness is one of the leading causes of fatal crashes. If you are not sure you are okay to drive — you are not okay to drive.

Do you have what you need? License, insurance card, registration. Some states allow digital versions, but always know where yours are.

Is the car ready? A quick walk-around. Tires look full. No obvious leaks. Mirrors clean. Lights working. Thirty seconds.

Plan the route. Set up navigation and music before you put the car in drive. Adjusting these while moving is how crashes happen.

Now, while you drive. Most responsible-driver habits live in this stage.

Wear your seatbelt. Every trip. Every seat. Seatbelts are the single most effective safety device in a car.

Put the phone away. Texting, scrolling, or even glancing at a notification takes your eyes off the road long enough to travel the length of a football field at highway speed. Use Do Not Disturb, or a similar mode.

Follow speed limits. They exist for the road, weather, and traffic conditions of that area. Going with the flow of traffic is not a legal defense if the flow is speeding.

Leave space. Tailgating gives you no time to react. A common guideline is at least a few seconds of following distance — more in bad weather.

Signal early. Other drivers can only cooperate with you if they know what you plan to do.

Yield when in doubt. Being right doesn''t matter if you''re in a crash.

Manage emotions. Frustration and anger behind the wheel lead to bad decisions. If another driver does something rude, let it go. Do not chase, brake-check, or escalate.

Let''s talk about passengers and distractions. Passengers are one of the biggest risk factors for new drivers. The more people in the car, the higher the crash risk — especially for teens.

Set expectations with friends. Phones go down. Voices stay calm. No messing with the wheel or controls.

You are responsible for what happens in the car. If passengers are being unsafe — pull over.

Pets should be secured. A loose animal can become a projectile in a crash, and is a major distraction.

When the weather is bad, the rules tighten. Rain, snow, ice, fog, and heavy wind all change what your car can do.

Slow down. Stopping distances grow on wet or icy roads.

Turn on headlights any time visibility drops, even during the day.

Increase following distance.

And if conditions are dangerous and the trip can wait — wait.

Responsibility also includes knowing what to do when things don''t go to plan.

If a warning light comes on, check the owner''s manual. Some lights mean schedule service soon. Others — oil pressure, engine temperature — mean pull over safely now.

If you break down, get the car as far off the road as possible, turn on hazards, and stay buckled inside if you are in a dangerous spot. Standing next to a car on a busy road is risky.

If you make a mistake, own it. Tell your parents. Tell your insurance company if needed. Hiding problems usually makes them bigger.

Here''s the bigger picture. When you drive, you are using a heavy, fast machine in a shared public space. The privilege comes with real obligations.

To the people in your car.

To other drivers, cyclists, and pedestrians who assume you will follow the rules.

To the community whose roads, signals, and emergency services make driving possible.

And to yourself, your future, and the people who care about you.

Responsible driving is not about being perfect. It is about taking the job seriously every time you sit in the driver''s seat. Do that — and the rest, including lower insurance costs, fewer scary moments, and a clean record, tends to follow.' WHERE id = 'lesson_insurance-and-responsibility_what-responsible-driving-looks-like';
